# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: albert-a-michelson
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:albert-a-michelson/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] The **1901 Nobel Prize in Physics** was presented in a ceremony in Stockholm, Sweden to the German Wilhelm Conrad Röntgen, "in recognition of the extraordinary services he has rendered by the discovery of the remarkable rays subsequently named after him", namely, X-rays.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] It was the first of its kind resulting from the will of the Swedish chemist Alfred Nobel in 1895 to recognize "the person who made the most important discovery or invention in the field of physics".
[src:albert-a-michelson/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] Wilhelm Röntgen (1845–1923) was a German physicist at the Ludwig-Maximilians-Universität München (LMU) and a member of the Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences when he received the Nobel Prize.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] Whilst he was at the University of Würzburg and experimenting with cathode ray tubes, Röntgen discovered on 8 November 1895 that some waves could penetrate objects and record their transparent likenesses on photographic plates.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] Röntgen announced his discoveries, which he named X-rays, in a brief note to the Physico-medical Society of Würzburg entitled *Eine neue Art von Strahlen* ("On a New Kind of Rays").
[src:albert-a-michelson/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] It immediately attracted enormous popular and scientific attention worldwide, with over one thousand books, pamphlets and articles appearing on the phenomenon, which Rudolph Albert von Kölliker dubbed "Röntgen rays", in just the year 1896.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] Deliberately left unpatented by Röntgen, by 1901, X-rays were seeing widespread use in hospitals, inspired further research into radiation, including among many future Nobel laureates, and made its discoverer into a celebrity.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] For instance, in 1900 alone, Röntgen received the Barnard Medal from Columbia University, and was made Knight of the Order of Merit of the Bavarian Crown and Prussian Order of the Crown 2nd Class.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] X-rays are still known in some languages as Röntgen rays, and images produced with them as roentgenograms.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] The Nobel Prize in Physics is awarded by an absolute majority vote of the Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences from among the persons given valid nominations by scientists and/or Academy members qualified to do so.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] The Academy held a plenary session on 12 November, with the secretary being Swedish chemist Wilhelm Palmær.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] There is no record of either proceedings or individual votes to comply with standards on secrecy.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] Within the Academy, there is a specialist Nobel Committee for Physics, usually composed of Swedes, who issue their own proposals and judgement.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] Röntgen was nominated by sixteen of the 29 nominators.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] Members of the Academy are denoted with an asterisk (*) in the table below.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] The five members of the Committee all divided their nominations between Röntgen and fellow German Philipp Lenard, who received the second-most number of nominations, i.e., six.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] Members of that Committee are denoted with a dagger (†).
[src:albert-a-michelson/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] Nominations must have been received before 1 February 1901.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] As was the case until 1910, the identity of the winners was not revealed until the prize ceremony the following month.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] Note that two of the nominees died between 1 February and the plenary session: Henry Augustus Rowland, on 16 April 1901, and Adolf Erik Nordenskiöld, on 12 August; therefore, they would be disqualified for a Nobel Prize, whose recipient must be living.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] Additionally, at least two nominations (including Rowland's) were disallowed because they were self-nominations.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] The Nobel Prize ceremonies began at 7 p.m. on Tuesday, 10 December 1901, the fifth anniversary of Nobel's death.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] As until 1926, the scientific Prizes were presented in the hall of the Royal Swedish Academy of Music in Nybroviken, Stockholm, Sweden.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] The presentation speeches for the Prizes in Physics and Chemistry were delivered by Clas Theodor Odhner, President of the Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences, and former Rector of the National Archives of Sweden.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] Röntgen was then presented with the Nobel diploma (designed by Sofia Gisberg) and medal from Crown Prince Gustaf, the future Gustaf V, in the King's absence.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] After the other medals were awarded, the laureates attended a banquet, held as until 1930 in the Grand Hôtel, Stockholm.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] Unlike the other laureates, Röntgen did not deliver a lecture the following day and left instead.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] In fact, he was intensely shy, refused interviews and resented publicity.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] In accordance with Nobel's will, the prize money was divided to the laureates from the income of safe investments made by the Nobel Foundation from his vast fortune.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] Accounting for inflation, this would be the most paid to a Nobel laureate until 1991.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] It is sometimes said that Röntgen donated this prize to the University of Würzburg after his death—while he did dedicate nearly that amount in his testament of 1920 (200,000 M), it was never specifically linked to the Nobel Prize.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] In any case, the hyperinflation of the German Mark contemporary with Röntgen's death in 1923 essentially made his bequest worthless.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] Despite the renown of Röntgen's invention, papers in the United States and the United Kingdom reported only cursorily on his receiving the Nobel Prize.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] Swedish press reports were more extensive.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] A number reprinted the faces and biographies of Röntgen and the other laureates.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] The *Stockholms Dagblad* commented on the laureates' "characteristic physiognomies", including Röntgen's "sharply defined face, projecting Teutonic strength with his long, bushy beard" (*skarpt skurna ansigte, verkande med teutonens kraft i det långa, yfviga skägget*).
[src:albert-a-michelson/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] The Motala *Tidning* commented that by the discovery of X-rays, Röntgen had earned "one of the foremost places of honour in the scientific world" (*en af de främsta hedersplatserna inom den vetenskapliga världen*).
[src:albert-a-michelson/1907-nobel-prize-in-literature] Rudyard Kipling praised the British colonial empire in his works as a poet, short story author, journalist, and novelist, which made his poetry well-liked in the British Army.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1907-nobel-prize-in-literature] Children all across the globe have grown to know and love him as a result of *The Jungle Book* (1894), especially because of Disney's 1967 motion picture adaptation.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1907-nobel-prize-in-literature] The Swedish Academy said that Kipling's human portraits and social environment descriptions that "penetrate to the substance of things" rather than merely repeating the fleeting" were his distinctive qualities.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1907-nobel-prize-in-literature] His classic literary works include *Kim* (1901), the *Just So Stories* (1902) and many short stories, including *The Man Who Would Be King* (1888).
[src:albert-a-michelson/1907-nobel-prize-in-literature] Kipling was nominated four times beginning in 1904.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1907-nobel-prize-in-literature] He was nominated in 1907 by Charles Oman, professor of modern history at the University of Oxford, which later led to him being awarded the Nobel prize.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1907-nobel-prize-in-literature] In total, the Swedish Academy received 37 nominations for 21 writers.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1907-nobel-prize-in-literature] The highest number of nominations – five nominations – were for the Italian writer Angelo de Gubernatis followed by American theologian Borden Parker Bowne with four nominations.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1907-nobel-prize-in-literature] Eight of the nominees were nominated first-time such as Holger Drachmann, Eduardo Benot, Andrés Manjón, Àngel Guimerà, and Paul Bourget.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1907-nobel-prize-in-literature] Selma Lagerlöf is the only female nominee for that year.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1907-nobel-prize-in-literature] The American writer Mark Twain was purportedly nominated in 1907 and 1908, but is not included in the archives.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1907-nobel-prize-in-literature] The British minister Ian Maclaren and Spanish academic Eduardo Benot died months before the announcement.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1907-nobel-prize-in-literature] In 1907, the Nobel committee proposed that the Nobel Prize in Literature should be awarded to the English author Rudyard Kipling, noting that "Kipling is a lover of concretion and concentration; one almost never finds in him empty abstractions and never paraphrases.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1907-nobel-prize-in-literature] He quickly finds the striking expression, the descriptive epithet.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1907-nobel-prize-in-literature] One does not notice a trace of imitation in him.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1907-nobel-prize-in-literature] The Nobel committee also made special mentions of the Catalan poet Àngel Guimerà y Jorge, English author Algernon Charles Swinburne, French writer Paul Bourget and Italian writer Antonio Fogazzaro as worthy candidates for the prize.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1907-nobel-prize-in-literature] Nobel committee member Carl David af Wirsén advocated a prize for Swinburne, but ultimately Wirsén chose to support Kipling's candidacy as a way of blocking Selma Lagerlöf, whose writing Wirsén disliked, from being awarded.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1907-nobel-prize-in-literature] The choice of Rudyard Kipling was very well received.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1907-nobel-prize-in-literature] Kipling was widely celebrated by both the Swedish press and public crowds when he arrived in Stockholm to accept the prize.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] The **1925 Santa Barbara earthquake** hit the area of Santa Barbara, California on June 29, with a moment magnitude between 6.5 and 6.8 and a maximum Mercalli Intensity of IX (*Violent*).
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] It resulted in 13 deaths and destroyed the historic center of the city, with damage estimated at $8 million (about $111 million in 2017).
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] Although no foreshocks were reported felt before the mainshock, a pressure gauge recording card at the local waterworks showed disturbances beginning at 3:27 a.m., which were likely caused by foreshocks.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] At 6:44 a.m. the mainshock occurred which lasted 19 seconds.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] The epicenter of the earthquake was located in the sea off the coast of Santa Barbara, in the Santa Barbara Channel.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] The fault on which it occurred appears to have been an extension of the Mesa fault or the Santa Ynez system.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] The earthquake was felt from Paso Robles (San Luis Obispo County) to the north to Santa Ana (Orange County) to the south and to Mojave (Kern County) to the east.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] Major damage occurred in the city of Santa Barbara and along the coast, as well as north of Santa Ynez Mountains, including Santa Ynez and Santa Maria valleys.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] Though thirteen people died, it might have been far worse without the actions of three heroes, who shut off the town gas and electricity and prevented a catastrophic fire.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] Most homes survived the earthquake in relatively good condition, although nearly every chimney in the city crumbled.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] The downtown of Santa Barbara was destroyed.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] Only a few buildings along State Street, the main commercial street, remained standing after the earthquake.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] The City Cab building and The Californian and Arlington garages, all large and fully occupied parking structures, collapsed full with cars.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] Many other vehicles were crushed in the downtown area.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] At least one death resulted when a driver near the San Marcos building was crushed as walls of buildings fell onto cars parked there.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] In the business district, an area of about 36 blocks, only a few structures were not substantially damaged, and many had to be completely demolished and rebuilt.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] The facade of the church of the Mission Santa Barbara was severely damaged and lost its statues.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] Many important buildings, including hotels, offices, and the Potter Theater, were lost.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] The courthouse, jail, library, schools, and churches were among the buildings sustaining serious damage.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] Concrete curbs buckled in almost every block in Santa Barbara.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] Pavement on the boulevard along the beach was displaced by about 20–36 centimeters (0.66–1.18 ft), but the pavement in the downtown generally was not damaged.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] The earthen Sheffield Dam had been built near the city in 1917.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] It was 720 feet (220 m) long and 25 feet (7.6 m) high and held 30 million US gallons (114 million liters) of water.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] The soil under the dam liquefied during the earthquake and the dam collapsed.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] This was the only dam to fail during an earthquake in the U.S. until the Lower Van Norman Dam failed in 1971.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] When it burst, a wall of water swept between Voluntario Street and Alisos Street, destroying trees, cars, three houses and flooding the lower part of town to a depth of 2 feet (0.61 m).
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] The Southern Pacific Company Railroad tracks were damaged in several places between Ventura and Gaviota.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] In particular, a portion between Naples and Santa Barbara was badly damaged and displaced.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] Seaside bluffs fell into the ocean, and a slight tsunami was noted by offshore ships.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] The town was completely cut off from telephone and telegraph, and news from the outside world arrived by shortwave radio.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] The absence of post-earthquake fire permitted scientists to study earthquake damage to various types of construction.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] The American Legion and the Naval Reserves from the Naval Reserve Center Santa Barbara helped provide order amidst the chaos and manned posts and provided patrols throughout the town to inhibit looting of the damaged businesses and homes.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] Additional fire and police personnel arrived from as far as Los Angeles to assist the sailors and soldiers in maintaining order.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] Three strong aftershocks occurred in the next few hours, though none causing any additional damage, with events occurring at 8:08, 10:45, and 10:57 am, and many smaller shocks continued throughout the day.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] An aftershock on July 3 caused additional cracked walls and damaged chimneys.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] Since the downtown of Santa Barbara suffered irreparable damage, there was a large-scale construction effort in 1925 and 1926 aimed at removing or repairing damaged structures and constructing new buildings.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] This development completely altered the character of the city center.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] Before the earthquake, a considerable part of the center was built in the Moorish Revival style.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] After the earthquake, the decision was made to rebuild it in the Spanish Colonial Revival style.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] This effort was undertaken by the Santa Barbara Community Arts Association, which was founded in the beginning of the 1920s and viewed the earthquake as the opportunity to rebuild the city center in the unified architectural style.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] Many architects were invited to design the building facades, among them Lionel Pries, James Osborne Craig, George Washington Smith, Carleton Winslow, Bertram Goodhue, and Winsor Soule.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] Pries moved his practice from San Francisco to Santa Barbara for a full year.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] As a result, many buildings later listed on National Register of Historic Places were designed in the late 1920s, among them the Santa Barbara County Courthouse and the front of the Andalucia Building.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] Building codes in Santa Barbara were made more stringent after the earthquake demonstrated that traditional construction techniques of unreinforced concrete, brick, and masonry were unsafe and unlikely to survive strong temblors.
[src:albert-a-michelson/1925-santa-barbara-earthquake] Almost a century later, in 2017, an AI program run by the United States Geological Survey (USGS) mistakenly sent out email alerts about the historic quake due to an engineer updating the quake's epicenter in the USGS records.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] The **United States Naval Districts** is a system created by the United States Navy to organize military facilities, numbered sequentially by geographic region, for the operational and administrative control of naval bases and shore commands in the United States and around the world.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Established in 1903, naval districts became the foundational system for organizing U.S. naval forces ashore during the 20th century.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] The term "Naval" forces includes United States Marine Corps and current United States Coast Guard units.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] About half of nearly 20 numbered naval districts, after decades of service as successful naval operational support commands, were merged or disestablished by the U.S.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] By 1999 the remaining U.S. naval districts were reorganized and renamed as Navy Regions, except for Naval District Washington DC.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Navy organization of 11 geographic regions is now administered under Commander, Naval Installations Command (CNIC) in Washington DC.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] United States Marine Corps naval infantry forces operating with the USN are supported by the naval district system.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Since 1903, USMC strength has grown immensely with combined-arms artillery, armor, and aviation capability, especially for expeditionary and amphibious warfare during World War I in Europe and World War II in the Pacific.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Although part of the Navy Department, the Marine Corps is a separate branch of the U.S. armed forces that now maintains its own organization of USMC support base locations.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] United States Coast Guard forces, responsible for U.S. maritime security, continue to operate today in nine USCG naval Districts, using a revised version of the original numbered United States Naval District map, consolidated under two USCG Area commands, CG Atlantic Area and CG Pacific Area.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] In 1903 the Department of the Navy first created 13 numbered U.S.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Naval Districts as a system to improve the naval defense of the U.S. coast and extended territories from foreign attack.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] The Secretary of the Navy ordered creation of a system of districts for "the purpose of decentralizing administrative functions with respect to the control of coastwise sea communications and shore activities in states and territories outside department headquarters in Washington DC".
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] (b) Administrative coordination of all naval activities, with specific exceptions, within the district and extended seaward waters thereof.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Navy Regulations article 1480 first laid down the boundary limits of naval districts, which were based on existing coastal lighthouse districts dating to 1838.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] "Those limits extend to seaward so far as to include the coastwise sea lanes" (art.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] The Navy specified that "each naval district shall be commanded by a designated commandant (an appointed admiral or captain), who is the direct representative of the Navy Department, including its bureaus and offices, in all matters affecting district activity" (Art.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] During World War I and World War II, the number of Naval Districts grew from thirteen to seventeen.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Navy District Plan** designated a major regional naval base or shipyard facility as headquarters for each district.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Some districts had no staff until after the outbreak of World War I during August 1914.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] In 1915, the newly formed United States Coast Guard also adopted the geographic organization of U.S.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Naval Districts for operations and administration of USCG bases, stations, cutters, aircraft, and boats.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Department of Treasury from 1790 to 1967, the USCG predecessor Lighthouse Board was the first maritime bureau to establish a district organization as directed by an 1838 act of Congress for steamboat safety.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Life Saving Service merged to become the U.S.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Coast Guard in 1915, the naval district map system was used to organize the combined service.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] In the Coast Guard naval district organization, USCG districts were placed in the CG Eastern Area or Western Area.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] The two Coast Guard Areas were each commanded by a USCG admiral senior to their district commanders.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Later, during World War II the Coast Guard military organization also absorbed three other legacy U.S. maritime safety agencies: the Steamboat Inspection Service, Bureau of Navigation, and U.S.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Navy fleet, as happened during World War I and World War II.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] From 1960 to 1980, the Navy closed several naval bases in the northeastern states.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] On 7 October 1976, First Naval District at the old Boston Naval Shipyard was disestablished and passed command to the Fourth Naval District in Philadelphia, PA.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] The New England states area of responsibility in the former First Naval District is now part of U.S.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Navy ship work at Philadelphia Naval Shipyard was decommissioned by early 2000, pursuant to recommendations by the Base Realignment and Closure commission, with the exception of supply depot logistics operations at Naval Support Activity Philadelphia.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] The northeastern states area of responsibility in the former Fourth Naval District is now part of U.S.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] By 1945, Naval Station Norfolk had grown enormously and also become headquarters for U.S.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Fifth Naval District boundaries included: West Virginia, Maryland (except 6 counties nearest the District of Columbia, Anne Arundel, Prince Georges, Montgomery, St.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Between 1960 and 1980, the Navy closed aging historic shipyards in the northeast United States and merged about half of the numbered naval districts for budgetary efficiency and military effectiveness.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Atlantic bases in the Hampton Roads, VA region, expanding since 1942, grew even larger with added ships, submarines, aircraft, and naval amphibious activities at bases like Little Creek, Dam Neck, and NAS Oceana in Virginia Beach.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] But on 30 September 1980, Fifth Naval District became one of six original numbered districts disestablished on that date.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] The large area of responsibility for 20 northeast and midwest states in the **former First, Second, Third, Fourth, and Fifth Naval Districts** is now part of U.S.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Sixth Naval District was disestablished along with the Fourth, Fifth and Tenth Naval Districts on 30 September 1980.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] But Charleston Shipyard remained a major naval installation throughout the Cold War as homeport to numerous Navy cruisers, destroyers, attack submarines, ballistic missile submarines, destroyer tenders, and submarine tenders of the U.S.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] The 1993 Base Realignment and Closure Commission report recommended final closure of the Naval Base on 1 April 1996.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] The south Atlantic states area of responsibility of the former Sixth Naval District command is now part of U.S.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] In 2020 the Coast Guard Commandant announced a USCG plan to station more new major cutters and enlarge shore operations facilities at Base Charleston during this decade, as a "future Coast Guard operational center of gravity" for Atlantic Area cutters homeported in **Seventh Coast Guard District**.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Eighth District is by far the largest Coast Guard District geographic area, with a secondary HQ base in St.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Louis MO supporting the inland western river system.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] The Eighth District map includes 26 states from Pennsylvania to Wyoming, through which flow many navigable western rivers, part of the vast inland waterways transportation system in the industrial and agricultural heartland of the United States.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] In 1993 the Base Realignment and Closure Commission recommended closing two of three U.S.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] RTC San Diego, CA and RTC Orlando, FL were shut down by 1999, making Recruit Training Command Great Lakes the sole Navy boot camp.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Naval training centers of the former Ninth Naval District and naval shore activities in the Great Lakes states and are now supported by Naval Service Training Command and by U.S.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Navy operational facilities in the Caribbean Sea have been significantly reduced since the 1990s, including Guantanamo, Cuba (GITMO) and Vieques, PR.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Many shore activities and fleet training in the Caribbean moved to naval bases around Jacksonville and Mayport, Florida.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Those facilities are now supported by Navy Region Southeast or United States Fleet Forces Command.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Navy and Marine Corps facilities, shore bases, and support commands in the southwestern United States from the former Eleventh Naval District are now part of Navy Region Southwest, headquartered in downtown San Diego, California.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Navy and Marine Corps facilities, shore bases, and support commands in the northwestern states from the former Thirteenth Naval District, plus Alaska, are now part of Navy Region Northwest, headquartered on Puget Sound at Naval Base Kitsap, WA.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] On 31 December 1975, Fifteenth Naval District was disestablished.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] It responsibilities were handed over to the U.S.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Naval Station Panama Canal, often known as Rodman Naval Station.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Under President Jimmy Carter's administration, the Panama Canal Zone was disestablished in 1979.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] In 1999, the United States closed military facilities in Panama and transferred control of bases and the Panama Canal to the government of Panama.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] From 1945 until 1992, this part of the southwest Pacific region was called U.S.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Naval Base Philippines, consisting of a number of naval stations located on the many islands in the Philippines, including the large Naval Base Subic Bay ship repair facility.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Most of these bases were shore support facilities built during World War II by Navy Seabee Construction Battalions as U.S. forces regained control of the islands from the Japanese Empire.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] In 1992 the United States returned all naval bases to the Philippine Navy, as well as closing other U.S. military facilities in the Philippines, including the large Clark Air Force Base.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Navy operations in the Philippines area are now supported by one of the Navy Regions in the western Pacific, such as Navy Region Center Singapore.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] In 2022 amid growing tensions with China, the United States and Philippine governments quietly began preparations for U.S. forces to return to the Subic Bay naval facility.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Navy and Marine Corps operations in the former Seventeenth Naval District of Alaska are now supported by Navy Region Northwest, headquartered on Puget Sound at Naval Base Kitsap, WA.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] In 2021, the Navy began considering re-opening Adak Air Station due to heightened global power competition with Russia and China.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Naval District Washington is one of eleven current U.S.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Navy commands re-organized as Regions in 1999, but NDW retained the naval district name.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] NDW operates and manages Naval shore installations in the Washington D.C.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Naval District Washington headquarters is located next to Commander, Navy Installations Command HQ in the historic Washington Navy Yard on the Anacostia River in southeast DC.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] The NDW Commandant is a Navy rear admiral who leads the oldest district that remains from the original 1903 Naval District system.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Navy asset in the National Capitol Region military district Joint Force Headquarters.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] JFHQ-NCR is responsible for homeland defense of the greater Washington, DC National Capital Region, including The Pentagon, Headquarters Marine Corps, U.S.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Coast Guard HQ, and all U.S. military facilities in the area.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Since the modern USCG was formed by the Coast Guard Act in 1915, USCG cutters, boats, aircraft, and shore forces have operated using a revised version of the original 1903 numbered naval district map.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] The former Coast Guard East and West Areas were renamed CG Atlantic Area and CG Pacific Area in the 1960s, with each Area command led by a USCG three star vice admiral.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] By 1987 the number of Coast Guard districts was reduced from 13 to 10 through several district mergers and many boundary line adjustments.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] When the Cold War ended in 1991, all U.S. military services down-sized force organizations, consolidated, and realigned bases.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] On 30 May 1996, Coast Guard Eighth District (Gulf of Mexico), and CG Second District (Mississippi & Ohio western river system) were combined to form the enlarged new Eighth Coast Guard District, leaving the Coast Guard organizational map with the current nine geographic districts.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] The two USCG Atlantic and Pacific Area Commanders are operationally responsible to the Commandant of the Coast Guard, the U.S. armed forces Joint Chiefs of Staff, and the Secretary of Homeland Security for coastal defense and the maritime security of the United States homeland.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Coast Guard District Commanders report to the two Area Commanders for homeland defense, and lead the training operations of part-time Coast Guard Reserve component forces, as well as U.S.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Navy Reserve training units assigned to coastal security duties in USCG Sectors.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] Coast Guard Auxiliary uniformed service volunteers organized in local civilian boat flotillas, who perform safety assistance patrols in each USCG naval district geography.
[src:albert-a-michelson/9th-naval-district] The Coast Guard Auxiliary District map adds sixteen sub-regions, aligned with USCG Sectors, that administratively support the U.S. recreational boating safety public outreach activities of thousands of CG Auxiliarists.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] Starting from Rainwater's concept of an irregular-shaped liquid drop model of the nucleus, Bohr and Mottelson developed a detailed theory that was in close agreement with experiments.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] Since his father, Niels Bohr, had won the prize in 1922, he and his father are one of the several pairs of fathers and sons who have both won the Nobel Prize.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] Bohr was born in Copenhagen on 19 June 1922, the fourth of six sons of the physicist Niels Bohr and his wife Margrethe Bohr (née Nørlund).
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] His oldest brother, Christian, died in a boating accident in 1934, and his youngest, Harald, was severely disabled and placed away from the home in Copenhagen at the age of four.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] He would later die from childhood meningitis.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] Of the others, Hans became a physician; Erik, a chemical engineer; and Ernest, a lawyer and Olympic athlete who played field hockey for Denmark at the 1948 Summer Olympics in London.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] The family lived at the Institute of Theoretical Physics at the University of Copenhagen, now known as the Niels Bohr Institute, where he grew up surrounded by physicists who were working with his father, such as Hans Kramers, Oskar Klein, Yoshio Nishina, Wolfgang Pauli and Werner Heisenberg.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] In 1932, the family moved to the Carlsberg Æresbolig, a mansion donated by Carl Jacobsen, the heir to Carlsberg breweries, to be used as an honorary residence by the Dane who had made the most prominent contribution to science, literature, or the arts.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] Bohr went to high school at Sortedam Gymnasium in Copenhagen.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] In 1940, shortly after the German occupation of Denmark in April, he entered the University of Copenhagen, where he studied physics.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] He assisted his father, helping draft correspondence and articles related to epistemology and physics.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] In September 1943, word reached his family that the Nazis considered them to be Jewish, because Bohr's grandmother, Ellen Adler Bohr, had been Jewish, and that they therefore were in danger of being arrested.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] The Danish resistance helped the family escape by sea to Sweden.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] Bohr arrived there in October 1943, and then flew to Britain on a de Havilland Mosquito operated by British Overseas Airways Corporation.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] The Mosquitoes were unarmed high-speed bomber aircraft that had been converted to carry small, valuable cargoes or important passengers.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] By flying at high speed and high altitude, they could cross German-occupied Norway, and yet avoid German fighters.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] Bohr, equipped with a parachute, flying suit, and oxygen mask, spent the three-hour flight lying on a mattress in the aircraft's bomb bay.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] On arrival in London, Bohr rejoined his father, who had flown to Britain the week before.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] He officially became a junior researcher at the Department of Scientific and Industrial Research, but actually served as personal assistant and secretary to his father.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] The two worked on Tube Alloys, the British atomic bomb project.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] On 30 December 1943, they made the first of a number of visits to the United States, where his father was a consultant to the Manhattan Project.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] Due to his father's fame, they were given false names; Bohr became James Baker, and his father, Nicholas Baker.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] In 1945, the director of the Los Alamos Laboratory, J.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] Robert Oppenheimer, asked them to review the design of the modulated neutron initiator.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] That they had reached this conclusion put Enrico Fermi's concerns about the viability of the design to rest.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] The initiators performed flawlessly in the bombs used in the atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki in August 1945.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] In August 1945, with the war ended, Bohr returned to Denmark, where he resumed his university education, graduating with a master's degree in 1946, with a thesis concerned with some aspects of atomic stopping power problems.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] In early 1948, Bohr became a member of the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton, New Jersey.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] While paying a visit to Columbia University, he met Isidor Isaac Rabi, who sparked in him an interest in recent discoveries related to the hyperfine structure of deuterium.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] This led to Bohr becoming a visiting fellow at Columbia from January 1949 to August 1950.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] While in the United States, Bohr married Marietta Soffer on 11 March 1950.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] They had three children: Vilhelm, Tomas and Margrethe.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] By the late 1940s it was known that the properties of atomic nuclei could not be explained by then-current models such as the liquid drop model developed by Niels Bohr amongst others.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] The shell model, developed in 1949 by Maria Goeppert Mayer and others, allowed some additional features to be explained, in particular the so-called magic numbers.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] However, there were also properties that could not be explained, including the non-spherical distribution of charge in certain nuclei.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] In a 1950 paper, James Rainwater of Columbia University suggested a variant of the drop model of the nucleus that could explain a non-spherical charge distribution.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] Rainwater's model postulated a nucleus like a balloon with balls inside that distort the surface as they move about.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] He discussed the idea with Bohr, who was visiting Columbia at the time, and had independently conceived the same idea, and had, about a month after Rainwater's submission, submitted for publication a paper that discussed the same problem, but along more general lines.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] Bohr imagined a rotating, irregular-shaped nucleus with a form of surface tension.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] Bohr developed the idea further, in 1951 publishing a paper that comprehensively treated the relationship between oscillations of the surface of the nucleus and the movement of the individual nucleons.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] Upon his return to Copenhagen in 1950, Bohr began working with Ben Roy Mottelson to compare the theoretical work with experimental data.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] In three papers, that were published in 1952 and 1953, Bohr and Mottelson demonstrated close agreement between theory and experiment; for example, showing that the energy levels of certain nuclei could be described by a rotation spectrum.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] They were thereby able to reconcile the shell model with Rainwater's concept.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] This work stimulated many new theoretical and experimental studies.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] Bohr, Mottelson and Rainwater were jointly awarded the 1975 Nobel Prize in Physics "for the discovery of the connection between collective motion and particle motion in atomic nuclei and the development of the theory of the structure of the atomic nucleus based on this connection".
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] Because his father had been awarded the prize in 1922, Bohr became one of only four pairs of fathers and sons to win the Nobel Prize in Physics.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] Only after doing his Nobel Prize-winning research did Bohr receive his doctorate from the University of Copenhagen, in 1954, writing his thesis on "Rotational States of Atomic Nuclei".
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] Bohr became a professor at the University of Copenhagen in 1956, and, following his father's death in 1962, succeeded him as director of the Niels Bohr Institute, a position he held until 1970.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] He remained active there until he retired in 1992.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] He was also a member of the board of the Nordic Institute for Theoretical Physics from its inception in 1957, and was its director from 1975 to 1981.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] In addition to the Nobel Prize, he won the Dannie Heineman Prize for Mathematical Physics in 1960, the Atoms for Peace Award in 1969, H.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] C. Ørsted Medal in 1970, Rutherford Medal and Prize in 1972, John Price Wetherill Medal in 1974, and the Ole Rømer medal in 1976.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] Bohr and Mottelson continued to work together, publishing a two-volume monograph, *Nuclear Structure*.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] The first volume, *Single-Particle Motion,* appeared in 1969; the second, *Nuclear Deformations,* in 1975.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] In 1972 Bohr was awarded an honorary degree, doctor philos. honoris causa, at the Norwegian Institute of Technology, later part of Norwegian University of Science and Technology.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] He was a member of the Norwegian Academy of Science and Letters from 1980.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] Bohr was also an elected member of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences, the American Philosophical Society, and the United States National Academy of Sciences.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] In 1981, Bohr became a founding member of the World Cultural Council.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] His son, Tomas Bohr, is a professor of physics at the Technical University of Denmark, working in the area of fluid dynamics.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] Aage Bohr died in Copenhagen on 8 September 2009.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] He was survived by his second wife and children.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] Bohr's Nobel Prize medal was sold at auction in November 2011.
[src:albert-a-michelson/aage-bohr] It was subsequently sold at auction in April 2019 for $90,000.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam was scientific advisor to the Ministry of Science and Technology in Pakistan from 1960 to 1974, a position from which he played a major and influential role in the development of the country's science infrastructure.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam contributed to numerous developments in theoretical and particle physics in Pakistan.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] He was the founding director of the Space and Upper Atmosphere Research Commission (SUPARCO), and responsible for the establishment of the Theoretical Physics Group (TPG).
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] For this, he is viewed as the "scientific father" of this program.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 1974, Abdus Salam departed from his country in protest after the Parliament of Pakistan unanimously passed a parliamentary bill declaring members of the Ahmadiyya Muslim community, to which Salam belonged, non-Muslim.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam's notable achievements include the Pati–Salam model, a Grand Unified Theory he proposed along with Jogesh Pati in 1974, magnetic photon, vector meson, work on supersymmetry and most importantly, electroweak theory, for which he was awarded the Nobel Prize.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam made a major contribution in quantum field theory and in the advancement of Mathematics at Imperial College London.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] With his student, Riazuddin, Salam made important contributions to the modern theory on neutrinos, neutron stars and black holes, as well as the work on modernising quantum mechanics and quantum field theory.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] As a teacher and science promoter, Salam is remembered as a founder and scientific father of mathematical and theoretical physics in Pakistan during his term as the chief scientific advisor to the president.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam heavily contributed to the rise of Pakistani physics within the global physics community.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Up until shortly before his death, Salam continued to contribute to physics, and to advocate for the development of science in third-world countries.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Abdus Salam was born on 29 January 1926 in Jhang in the Punjab Province of British India (present day in Pakistan) into a Punjabi family professing Ahmadiyya.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] He belonged to the Muslim Rajput community, his son Ahmad Salam later recounted that he would tell him stories of Rajput cultural history "of which he was very proud".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Jagjit Singh, in his biography of Salam, says that his family traditionally traced its genealogy back to a Rajput prince named Buddahn who converted to Islam at the hands of a Sufi preacher and later founded the city of Jhang around the year 1160.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam was the son of Chaudhary Muhammad Hussain, a school teacher of Jhang and Hajirah who belonged to Faizullah Chak near Batala.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] The name Choudhary Muhammad Hussain gave his son was Abd al-Salam which means "Servant of God".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Abd means servant and Salam is one of the 99 names of God in the Qur'an.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In English, his name is usually transliterated as Abdus Salam, which should be understood as a single given name.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] His father followed the custom of not giving a surname.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Later in his life he added Mohammad to his name.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam established an early reputation in Punjab for outstanding academic performance.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] At age 14, he scored the highest marks ever recorded for the entrance examination of the Punjab University, earning a full scholarship to the Government College of Lahore.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Instead of moving to Lahore immediately, he remained in Jhang and studied for two years at Government Intermediate College.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 1942, he passed his FA examinations with the highest scores in the province.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 1942, Salam moved to Lahore to study at Government College.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] As a fourth-year student, he published an elegant solution for a mathematical problem originally studied by Srinivasa Ramanujan.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 1944, his mathematics exam results set a new Punjab record.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam also excelled in Urdu and English literature, which could have led him to pursue further studies in English.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] However, on the recommendation of a mentor, he chose to continue with an M.A. in mathematics.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] At his father's urging, Salam attempted to enter the Indian Civil Service (ICS), considered the most prestigious career path for young graduates.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] He applied to the Indian Railways but was rejected after failing the medical optical tests; examiners also ruled that he was too young to qualify.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam remained in Lahore, completing his M.A. in mathematics at Government College in 1946 with record marks.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] That same year, he was awarded a scholarship to St John's College, Cambridge, where he enrolled in the undergraduate Mathematical Tripos and graduated in 1949 with a Double First-Class Honours in Mathematics and Physics.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Although his M.A. from Lahore would have qualified him to proceed directly to research, he still intended at that stage to pursue the ICS, and was advised to obtain a Cambridge mathematics degree first.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 1950, he received the Smith's Prize from Cambridge University for the most outstanding pre-doctoral contribution to Physics.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] After finishing his degrees, Fred Hoyle advised Salam to spend another year in the Cavendish Laboratory to do research in experimental physics, but Salam had no patience for carrying out long experiments in the laboratory.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam returned to Jhang and renewed his scholarship and returned to the United Kingdom to do his doctorate.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] While at Cavendish, Salam entered a Ph.D program.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] His doctoral thesis titled "Developments in quantum theory of fields" contained comprehensive and fundamental work in quantum electrodynamics.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] By the time it was published in 1951, it had already gained him an international reputation and the Adams Prize.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] During his doctoral studies, his mentors challenged him to solve within one year an intractable problem which had defied such great minds as Paul Dirac and Richard Feynman.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Within six months, Salam had found a solution for the renormalization of meson theory.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] As he proposed the solution at the Cavendish Laboratory, Salam had attracted the attention of Hans Bethe, J.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] After receiving his doctorate in 1951, Salam returned to Lahore at the Government College University as a professor of mathematics, where he remained till 1954.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 1952, he was appointed professor and chair of the Department of Mathematics at the neighbouring University of the Punjab.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In the latter capacity, Salam sought to update the university curriculum, introducing a course in quantum mechanics.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] He began to supervise the education of students who were particularly influenced by him.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] As a result, Riazuddin remained the only student of Salam who had the privilege to study under Salam at the undergraduate and post-graduate level in Lahore, and post-doctoral level in Cambridge University.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 1953, Salam was unable to establish a research institute in Lahore, as he faced strong opposition from his peers.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam went back to Cambridge and joined St John's College.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] During 1957, his tenure at Imperial College, London started.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] As time passed, this department became one of the prestigious research departments that included well known physicists such as Steven Weinberg, Tom Kibble, Gerald Guralnik, C.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] At Cambridge and Imperial College he formed a group of theoretical physicists, the majority of whom were his Pakistani students.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] At age 33, Salam became one of the youngest persons to be elected a Fellow of the Royal Society (FRS) in 1959.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam took a fellowship at the Princeton University in 1959, where he met with J.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Robert Oppenheimer and to whom he presented his research work on neutrinos.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Oppenheimer and Salam discussed the foundation of electrodynamics, problems and their solution.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] His dedicated personal assistant was Jean Bouckley.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 1980, Salam became a foreign fellow of the Bangladesh Academy of Sciences.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam made an important and significant contribution in Particle physics.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In his early career in Pakistan, Salam was greatly interested in mathematical series and their relation to physics.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam had played an influential role in the advancement of nuclear physics, but he maintained and dedicated himself to mathematics and theoretical physics and focused Pakistan to do more research in theoretical physics.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] However, he regarded nuclear physics (nuclear fission and nuclear power) as a non-pioneering part of physics as it had already "happened".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Even in Pakistan, Salam was the leading driving force in theoretical physics, with many scientists he continued to influence and encourage to keep their work on theoretical physics.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam had a prolific research career in theoretical and high-energy physics.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam had worked on the neutrino with his chiral symmetry.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam later passed his work to Riazuddin, who made pioneering contributions in neutrinos.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam introduced the massive Higgs bosons to the theory of the Standard Model, where he later predicted the existence of proton decay.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 1962, Salam published his theoretical work on the vector meson.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 1961, Salam began to work with John Clive Ward on symmetries and electroweak unification.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 1964, Salam and Ward worked on a Gauge theory for the weak and electromagnetic interaction, subsequently obtaining SU(2) × U(1) model.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam was convinced that all the elementary particle interactions are actually the gauge interactions.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 1968, together with Weinberg and Sheldon Glashow, Salam formulated the mathematical concept of their work.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] While in Imperial College, Salam, along with Glashow and Jeffrey Goldstone, mathematically proved the Goldstone's theorem, that a massless spin-zero object must appear in a theory as a result of spontaneous breaking of a continuous global symmetry.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 1967-8, Salam and Weinberg incorporated the Higgs mechanism into Glashow's discovery, giving it a modern form in electroweak theory, and thus theorised half of the Standard Model.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 1968, together with Weinberg and Sheldon Glashow, Salam finally formulated the mathematical concept of their work.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 1966, Salam carried out pioneering work on a hypothetical particle.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam showed the possible electromagnetic interaction between the Magnetic monopole and the C-violation, thus he formulated the magnetic photon.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Following the publication of PRL Symmetry Breaking papers in 1964, Steven Weinberg and Salam were the first to apply the Higgs mechanism to electroweak symmetry breaking.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam provided a mathematical postulation for the interaction between the Higgs boson and the electroweak symmetry theory.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 1972, Salam began to work with Indian-American theoretical physicist Jogesh Pati.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Pati wrote to Salam several times expressing interest to work under Salam's direction, in response to which Salam eventually invited Pati to the ICTP seminar in Pakistan.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam suggested to Pati that there should be some deep reason why the protons and electrons are so different and yet carry equal but opposite electric charge.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Protons are composed of quarks, but the electroweak theory was concerned only with the electrons and neutrinos, with nothing postulated about quarks.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] If all of nature's ingredients could be brought together in one new symmetry, it might reveal a reason for the various features of these particles and the forces they feel.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] This led to the development of Pati–Salam model in particle physics.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam had worked on forces from 1959 with Glashow and Weinberg.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Glashow had also formulated the same work, and the theory was combined in 1966.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 1967, Salam proved the electroweak unification theory mathematically, and finally published the papers.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] For this achievement, Salam, Glashow, and Weinberg were awarded the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1979.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] The Nobel Prize Foundation paid tribute to the scientists and issued a statement saying: "For their contributions to the theory of the unified weak and electromagnetic interaction between elementary particles, including, inter alia, the prediction of the weak neutral current".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Only one known official replica of the Nobel Prize Medal was ever produced by the Mint of Pakistan in 1979/80.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] This medal has a large test cut and damage from two to three o'clock.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] The replica medal was sold at auction to an unknown bidder on April 23, 2025.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In the 1970s Salam continued trying to unify forces by including the strong interaction in a Grand Unified Theory.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 1961 he approached President Khan to set up the country's first national space agency, thus on 16 September 1961 the Space and Upper Atmosphere Research Commission was established, with Salam as its first director.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Before 1960, very little work on scientific development was done, and scientific activities in Pakistan were almost diminished.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam called Ishfaq Ahmad, a nuclear physicist, who had left for Switzerland where he joined CERN, back to Pakistan.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] With the support of Salam, PAEC established PAEC Lahore Center-6, with Ishfaq Ahmad as its first director.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 1967, Salam became a central and administrative figure to lead the research in Theoretical and Particle physics.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] With the establishment of the Institute of Physics at Quaid-e-Azam University, research in theoretical and particle physics was engaged.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Under Salam's direction, physicists tackled the greatest outstanding problems in physics and mathematics and their physics research reached a point that prompted worldwide recognition of Pakistani physicists.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] From the 1950s, Salam had tried establishing high-powered research institutes in Pakistan, though he was unable to do so.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] He moved PAEC Headquarters to a bigger building, and established research laboratories all over the country.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] On the direction of Salam, Ishrat Hussain Usmani set up plutonium and uranium exploration committees throughout the country.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In October 1961, Salam travelled to the United States and signed a space co-operation agreement between Pakistan and US.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In November 1961, the US National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) started to build a space facility – Flight Test Center (FTC) – at Sonmiani, a coastal town in Balochistan Province.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam served as its first technical director.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] While in the IAEA, Salam had consulted about the establishment of the International Centre for Theoretical Physics (ICTP), a research physics institution, in Trieste, Italy...
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam obtained permission from President Ayub Khan to set up the Karachi Nuclear Power Plant.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Also in 1965, led by Salam, the United States and Pakistan signed an agreement in which the US provided Pakistan with a small research reactor (PARR-I).
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam had a long-held dream to establish a research institute in Pakistan, which he had advocated for on many occasions.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 1965 again, Salam and architect Edward Durell Stone signed a contract for the establishment of the Pakistan Institute of Nuclear Science and Technology (PINSTECH) at Nilore, Islamabad.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In early 1961, Salam approached President Khan to lay the foundations of Pakistan's first executive agency to co-ordinate space research.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] By executive order on 16 September 1961 the Space and Upper Atmosphere Research Commission (SUPARCO) was established with Salam founding director.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam knew the importance of nuclear technology in Pakistan, for civilian and peaceful purposes.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] But, according to his biographers, Salam played an ambiguous role in Pakistan's own atomic bomb project.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] As late as the 1960s, Salam made an unsuccessful proposal for the establishment of a nuclear fuel reprocessing plant, but it was deferred on economic grounds by Ayub Khan.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] According to Rehman, Salam's influence in nuclear development was diminished as late as 1974, and he became critical of Bhutto's control over science.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] But Salam personally did not terminate his connection with the scientists working in the theoretical physics division at PAEC.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] As early as 1972–73, he had been a great advocate for the atomic bomb project, but subsequently took a stance against it after he fell out with Bhutto over the Second Amendment to the Constitution of Pakistan which declared the Ahmaddiya denomination to be non-Islamic.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 1965, Salam led the establishing of the nuclear research institute – PINSTECH.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 1965, the plutonium Pakistan Atomic Research Reactor (PARR-I) went critical under Salams' leadership.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 1973, Salam proposed the idea of establishing an annual college to promote scientific activities in the country to the chairman of PAEC, Munir Khan, who accepted and fully supported the idea.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] This led to the establishment of the International Nathiagali Summer College on Physics and Contemporary Needs (INSC), where each year since 1976 scientists from all over the world come to Pakistan to interact with local scientists.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] The first annual INSC conference was held on advanced particle and nuclear physics.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In November 1971, Salam met with Zulfikar Ali Bhutto in his residence, and following Bhutto's advice, went to the United States to avoid the Indo-Pakistani War of 1971.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam travelled to the US and returned to Pakistan with scientific literature about the Manhattan Project, and calculations involving atomic bombs.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 1972, the Government of Pakistan learned about the development status of the first atomic bomb completed under the Indian nuclear programme.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] On 20 January 1972, Salam, as Science Advisor to the president of Pakistan, managed and participated in a secret meeting of nuclear scientists with former prime minister, Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, in Multan, known as the 'Multan Meeting'.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] At this meeting Bhutto orchestrated the development of a deterrence programme.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Usmani protested, believing that the country had neither the facilities or talent to carry out such an ambitious and technologically demanding project, whilst Salam remained quiet.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Here, Bhutto entrusted Salam and appointed Munir Khan as Chairman of PAEC, and head of the atomic bomb program, as Salam had supported Khan.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] A few months after the meeting, Salam, Khan, and Riazuddin, met with Bhutto in his residence where the scientists briefed him about the nuclear weapons program.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] After the meeting, Salam established the 'Theoretical Physics Group' (TPG) in PAEC.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam led groundbreaking work at TPG until 1974.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] An office was set up for Salam in the Prime Ministers' Secretariat by order of Bhutto.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam immediately started to motivate and invite scientists to begin work with PAEC in the development of fission weapons.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In December 1972, two theoretical physicists working at the International Centre for Theoretical Physics were asked by Salam to report to Munir Ahmad Khan, the scientific director of the program.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] This marked the beginning of the TPG, reporting directly to Salam.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] The TPG, in PAEC, was assigned to conduct research in fast neutron calculations, hydrodynamics (how the explosion produced by a chain reaction might behave), problems of neutron diffusion, and the development of theoretical designs of Pakistan's nuclear weapon devices.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Later, the TPG under Riazuddin began to directly report to Salam, and the work on the theoretical design of the nuclear weapon was completed in 1977.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 1972, Salam formed the Mathematical Physics Group, under Raziuddin Siddiqui, that was charged, with TPG, with carrying out research in the theory of simultaneity during the detonation process, and the mathematics involved in the theory of nuclear fission.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Following India's surprise nuclear test – Pokhran-I – in 1974, Munir Ahmad Khan had called a meeting to initiate work on an atomic bomb.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam was there and Muhammad Hafeez Qureshi was appointed head of the Directorate of Technical Development (DTD) in PAEC.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] The DTD was set up to co-ordinate the work of the various specialised groups of scientists and engineers working on different aspects of the atomic bomb.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] The word "bomb" was never used in this meeting, but the participants fully understood what was being discussed.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In March 1974, Salam and Khan also established the Wah Group Scientist that was charged with manufacturing materials, explosive lenses and triggering mechanism development of the weapon.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Following the setting up of DTD, Salam, Riazuddin and Munir Ahmad Khan, visited the Pakistan Ordnance Factories (POF) where they held talks with senior military engineers led by POF chairman Lieutenant-General Qamar Ali Mirza.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] It was there that the Corps of Engineers built the Metallurgical Laboratory in Wah Cantonment in 1976.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam remained associated with the nuclear weapons programme until mid-1974, when he left the country after Ahmadi were declared non-Muslims by the Pakistani Parliament.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] His own relations with Prime minister Bhutto fell out and turned into open hostility after the Ahmadiyya Community was declared as not-Islamic; he lodged a public and powerful protest against Bhutto regarding this issue and gave great criticism to Bhutto over his control over science.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In spite of this, Salam maintained close relations with the theoretical physics division at PAEC who kept him informed about the status of the calculations needed to calculate the performance of the atomic bomb, according to Norman Dombey.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In the 1980s, Salam personally approved many appointments and a large influx of Pakistani scientists to the associateship program at ICTP and CERN, and engaged in research in theoretical physics with his students at the ICTP.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 1964, Salam founded the International Centre for Theoretical Physics (ICTP), Trieste, in Italy and served as its director until 1993.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 1974, he founded the International Nathiagali Summer College (INSC) to promote science in Pakistan.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] The INSC is an annual meeting of scientists from all over the world who come to Pakistan and hold discussions on physics and science.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Even today, the INSC holds annual meetings, and Salam's pupil Riazuddin has been its director since its start.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 1997, the scientists at ICTP commemorated Salam and renamed ICTP as the "Abdus Salam International Centre for Theoretical Physics".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Throughout the years, he served on a number of United Nations committees concerning science and technology in developing countries.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam also founded the Third World Academy of Sciences (TWAS) and was a leading figure in the creation of a number of international centres dedicated to the advancement of science and technology.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 1979, Salam said: *Physicists believed there are four fundamental forces of nature; the gravitational force, the weak and strong nuclear force, and the electromagnetic force*.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 1981, Salam became a founding member of the World Cultural Council.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Although Salam left Pakistan, he did not terminate his connection to home.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] He continued inviting Pakistan's scientists to ICTP, and maintained a research programme for them.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Abdus Salam was a very private individual, who kept his public and personal lives quite separate.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] He married twice; first time to a cousin, the second time as well in accordance with Islamic law.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] At his death, he was survived by three daughters and a son by his first wife, and a son and daughter by his second, Professor Dame Louise Johnson, formerly Professor of molecular biophysics at Oxford University.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Two of his daughters are Anisa Bushra Salam Bajwa and Aziza Rahman.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam was an Ahmadi Muslim, who saw his religion as a fundamental part of his scientific work.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 1974, the Pakistan parliament made the Second Amendment to the Constitution of Pakistan that declared Ahmadis to be non-Muslim.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In protest, Salam left Pakistan for London.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] After his departure, he did not completely cut his ties to Pakistan, and kept a close association with the Theoretical Physics Group as well as academic scientists from the Pakistan Atomic Energy Commission.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Abdus Salam died on 21 November 1996 at the age of 70 in Oxford, England, from progressive supranuclear palsy.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] His body was returned to Pakistan and kept in Darul Ziafat, where some 13,000 men and women visited to pay their last respects.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Approximately 30,000 people attended his funeral prayers.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam was buried in Bahishti Maqbara, a cemetery established by the Ahmadiyya Muslim Community at Rabwah, Punjab, Pakistan, next to his parents' graves.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] The epitaph on his tomb initially read "First Muslim Nobel Laureate".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] The Pakistani government removed "Muslim" and left only his name on the headstone.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] It is the only nation to officially declare that Ahmadis are non-Muslim.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] The word "Muslim" was initially obscured on the orders of a local magistrate before moving to the national level.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Under Ordinance XX of 1984, being an Ahmadi, he was considered a non-Muslim according to the definition provided in the Second Amendment to the Constitution of Pakistan.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam's work in Pakistan has been far reaching and regarded as highly influential.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] He is remembered by his peers and students as the "father of Pakistan's school of Theoretical Physics" as well as Pakistan's science.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam was a charismatic and iconic figure, a symbol among them of what they were working or researching toward in their fields.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] His students, fellow scientists and engineers, remembered him as brilliant teacher, and engaging researcher who would also influence others to do the same.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] The International Centre for Theoretical Physics established by Salam has continued to train scientists from developing countries.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam founded the Space Research Commission of and was its first director.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 1998, the Government of Pakistan issued a commemorative stamp to honour Salam as part of its "Scientists of Pakistan" series.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] His alma mater, Government College Lahore, now a university, has the *Abdus Salam Chair in Physics* and Abdus Salam School of Mathematical Sciences named after him.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] *The Abdus Salam Chair* was also established in his honour at the Syed Babar Ali School of Science and Engineering in the Lahore University of Management Sciences.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] He made a significant contribution towards the 2012 success in the search for the Higgs boson.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In August 1996 another lifelong friend, Munir Ahmad Khan, met Salam in Oxford.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] A 1997 quote by Khan was "[We] Pakistanis may choose to ignore Dr.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] However, Salam's legacy is often ignored in the Pakistani education system despite his achievements.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] According to the documentary 'Salam: The First ****** Nobel Laureate,' very few young Pakistanis have heard of him, and his name is not mentioned in Pakistani school textbooks.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 2020, a group of students belonging to the State Youth Parliament desecrated an image of Salam that was present at a college in Gujranwala, while chanting slogans against the Ahmadiyya Muslim community.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] This deliberate effort to stifle mention of Salam is attributed to Salam belonging to the Ahmadiyya Muslim community, who have faced state-sponsored discrimination since the 1970s.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] LLC started formally researching and developing a film on the science and life of Abdus Salam in 2004, two years after the producers had conceived of the idea.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] A fundraising teaser was released by Kailoola Productions to coincide with Salam's birth anniversary on 29 January 2017.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] The post-production phase of this documentary film, pending funding, is estimated at US$150,000.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] The film *Salam: The First ****** Nobel Laureate*, directed by the Indian-American documentary filmmaker Anand Kamalakar, was announced in 2018 and released on Netflix in October 2019.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Pilgrim Films released *The Dream of Symmetry* in September 2011.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Their press release describes it as presenting "the extraordinary figure of Abdus Salam, who not only was an outstanding scientist but also a generous humanitarian and a valuable person.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam was elected to the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1971, the United States National Academy of Sciences in 1979, and the American Philosophical Society in 1992.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 1997, scientists at ICTP renamed the institute as the Abdus Salam International Centre for Theoretical Physics in the honour of Salam.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam's services have been recognised in Pakistan, as his students have openly spoken and stressed the importance of Science and Technology in Pakistan.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 1999, per the recommendation of Ishfaq Ahmad, the Government of Pakistan led the establishment of the Abdus Salam Chair in Physics at the Government College University.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] On 22 November 2009, the director of the Abdus Salam International Centre for Theoretical Physics gifted the original Nobel Prize Certificate to his alma mater.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 2011, GCU's Salam Chair in Physics held a one-day-long conference that was attributed to Abdus Salam.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam's students Ghulam Murtaza, Pervez Hoodbhoy, Riazuddin and Tariq Zaidi discussed the life and works of Salam, and brought to light his achievements in Pakistan and Physics.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] While covering the media converge on Salam's tribute, *The News International*, referred to Salam as the "great Pakistan scientist".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Bouchet-ICTP Institute was renamed as the Edward Bouchet Abdus Salam Institute.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 2003, the Government of Punjab created an institute of excellence for the Mathematical Sciences, the Abdus Salam School of Mathematical Sciences, in Salam's Alma mater – Government College University.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 2008, in an opinion piece, *Daily Times* called Salam "one of the greatest scientists Pakistan has ever produced".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 2015, the Academy of Young Researchers and Scholars, Lahore, renamed its library as the "Abdus Salam Library".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In the town of Vaughan, Ontario, Canada, near the headquarters of the Canadian branch of the Ahmadiyya Muslim Community, of which Abdus Salam was a member, the community has named a street after him, 'Abdus Salam Street', while at CERN in Geneva, Switzerland there is 'Route Salam'.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Additionally, there are two annual Abdus Salam science fairs, one held in Canada and the other in the US.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Each is organised as a National event for young scientists from the Ahmadiyya Muslim Community in an effort to motivate youth toward scientific endeavour.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] On 6 December 2016, Pakistan's prime minister Nawaz Sharif approved the renaming of Quaid-i-Azam University's (QAU) physics centre to the Professor Abdus Salam Center for Physics.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] It was also announced that the *Professor Abdus Salam Fellowship* will be established, which will include five annual fully funded Pakistani PhD students in the field of Physics in "leading international universities".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In November 2020, English Heritage erected a blue plaque in Salam's honour in Campion Road, Putney, London, at the house that was his London home for almost 40 years.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In June 2023, Imperial College, London announced the renaming of its Imperial College Central Library as the Abdus Salam Library.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 1979, Salam was awarded a third of the 1979 Nobel Prize in Physics, along with Glashow and Weinberg, *For their contributions to the theory of the unified weak and electromagnetic interaction between elementary particles, including, inter alia, the prediction of the weak neutral current*.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam received high civil and science awards from all over the world.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam is recipient of first high civil awards – Star of Pakistan.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Below is the list of awards that were conferred to Salam in his lifetime.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] The Abdus Salam Award (also called the Salam Prize) is an award established to recognise high achievements and contributions in physical and natural sciences.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] In 1979, Riazuddin, Fayyazuddin and Asghar Qadir met with Salam, and presented the idea of creating an award to appreciate scientists, resident in Pakistan, in their respective fields.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam donated the money he had won as he felt that he had no right use for the prize money.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] It was endowed by Asghar Qadir, Riazuddin and Fayyazuddin in 1980, and it was first awarded in 1981.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] The winners are selected by a committee (consisted of Aghar Qadir, Fayyazuddin, Riazuddin, and others) of the Center for Advanced Mathematics and Physics (CAMP), which administers the award.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] The Abdus Salam Medal is presented by the Third World Academy of Sciences in Trieste, Italy.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] First given in 1995, the award is presented to the people who have served the cause of science in the Developing World.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] The Abdus Salam Shield of Honor in Mathematics was initiated by the National Mathematical Society of Pakistan to promote and recognize quality research in Mathematics in 2015.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] It was awarded for the first time in 2016.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abdus-salam] Salam's primary focus was research on the physics of elementary particles.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Born in a one-room log cabin in Kentucky, Lincoln was raised on the frontier.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] He was self-educated and became a lawyer, Illinois state legislator, and U.S. representative.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Angered by the Kansas–Nebraska Act of 1854, which opened the territories to slavery, he became a leader of the new Republican Party.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] He reached a national audience in the 1858 Senate campaign debates against Stephen A.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln won the 1860 presidential election, becoming the first Republican president.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] His victory prompted a majority of the slave states to begin seceding and form the Confederate States.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] A month after Lincoln assumed the presidency, Confederate forces attacked Fort Sumter, starting the Civil War.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] As a moderate Republican, Lincoln had to navigate conflicting political opinions from contentious factions during the war effort.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] He closely supervised the Union's strategy and tactics, including the selection of generals and the implementation of a naval blockade of Southern ports.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] He suspended the writ of *habeas corpus* in April 1861, an action that Chief Justice Roger Taney found in *Ex parte Merryman* that only Congress could do, and he averted war with Britain by defusing the *Trent* Affair.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] On January 1, 1863, he issued the Emancipation Proclamation, which declared the slaves in the states "in rebellion" to be free.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] On November 19, 1863, he delivered the Gettysburg Address, which became one of the most famous speeches in American history.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] He promoted the Thirteenth Amendment to the U.S.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Constitution, which, in 1865, abolished chattel slavery.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Following his re-election in 1864, he sought to heal the war-torn nation through Reconstruction.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] On April 14, 1865, five days after the Confederate surrender at Appomattox, Lincoln was fatally shot by John Wilkes Booth at Ford's Theatre in Washington, D.C., becoming the first U.S. president to be assassinated.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln is remembered as a martyr and a national hero for his wartime leadership and for his efforts to preserve the Union and abolish slavery.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] He is consistently ranked in both popular and scholarly polls as among the greatest presidents in American history.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Born in a one-room log cabin in Kentucky on February 12, 1809, Abraham Lincoln was raised on Sinking Spring Farm near Hodgenville, Kentucky.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] The captain was killed in a Native American raid in 1786.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] The family settled in Hardin County, Kentucky, in the early 1800s.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Nancy is widely assumed to have been the daughter of Lucy Hanks.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Thomas and Nancy married on June 12, 1806, and moved to Elizabethtown, Kentucky.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] They had three children: Sarah, Abraham, and Thomas Jr., who died as an infant.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's father bought multiple farms in Kentucky but could not get clear property titles to any, losing hundreds of acres in legal disputes.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1816, the family moved to Indiana, where land titles were more reliable.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] They settled on a forested plot in Little Pigeon Creek Community.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] In Kentucky and Indiana, Thomas worked as a farmer, cabinetmaker, and carpenter.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] At various times, he owned farms, livestock, and town lots, appraised estates, and served on county patrols.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Thomas and Nancy were members of a Separate Baptist Church, a pious evangelical group whose members largely opposed slavery.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Overcoming financial challenges, Thomas obtained clear title to 80 acres (32 ha) in Little Pigeon Creek Community in 1827.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] On October 5, 1818, Nancy died from milk sickness, leaving 11-year-old Sarah in charge of the household, which included her father, 9-year-old Abraham, and Nancy's 19-year-old orphan cousin, Dennis Hanks.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Thomas married Sarah Bush Johnston, a widow with three children of her own, on December 2, 1819.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Abraham became close to his stepmother and called her "Mama".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] On January 20, 1828, Lincoln's sister died in childbirth, devastating him.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] His formal schooling was from itinerant teachers.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] It included two short stints in Kentucky, where he learned to read, but probably not to write.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] After moving to Indiana at age seven, he attended school only sporadically, for a total of less than 12 months by age 15.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Nevertheless, he was an avid reader and maintained a lifelong interest in learning.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] When Lincoln was a teenager his father relied heavily on him for farmwork and for supplementary income, hiring the boy out to area farmers and pocketing the money, as was the custom at the time.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] When he was somewhat older, Lincoln and some friends took a job carrying goods by flatboat to New Orleans, Louisiana, where the slave markets, according to the historian Michael Burlingame, "would leave an indelible impression on him....
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] In March 1830, fearing another milk-sickness outbreak, several members of the extended Lincoln family, including Abraham, moved west to Illinois and settled in Macon County.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Abraham became increasingly distant from Thomas, in part due to his father's lack of interest in education; he would later refuse to attend his father's deathbed or funeral in 1851.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Some historians, such as Michael Burlingame, identify Lincoln's first romantic interest as Ann Rutledge, a young woman also from Kentucky whom he met when he moved to New Salem, Illinois.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lewis Gannett disputes that the evidence supports a romantic relationship between the two.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] David Herbert Donald states that "How that friendship [between Lincoln and Rutledge] developed into a romance cannot be reconstructed from the record".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Rutledge died on August 25, 1835, of typhoid fever.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln took her death very hard, sinking into a serious depression and contemplating suicide.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] In the early 1830s, Lincoln met Mary Owens from Kentucky.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Late in 1836, Lincoln agreed to a match with Owens if she returned to New Salem.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Owens arrived that November and he courted her, but they both had second thoughts.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] On August 16, 1837, he wrote Owens a letter saying he would not blame her if she ended the relationship, and she declined to marry him.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1839, Lincoln met Mary Todd in Springfield, Illinois, and the following year they became engaged.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] She was a daughter of Robert Smith Todd, a wealthy lawyer and businessman in Lexington, Kentucky.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln initially broke off the engagement in early 1841, but the two were reconciled and married on November 4, 1842.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1844, the couple bought a house in Springfield near his law office.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] The marriage was turbulent; Mary was verbally abusive and at times physically violent towards her husband.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] The eldest, Robert Todd Lincoln, was born in 1843, and was the only child to live to maturity.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Edward Baker "Eddie" Lincoln, born in 1846, died February 1, 1850, probably of tuberculosis.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's third son, William Wallace "Willie" Lincoln, was born on December 21, 1850, and died of a fever at the White House on February 20, 1862.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] The youngest, Thomas "Tad" Lincoln, was born on April 4, 1853, and died of edema at age 18 on July 16, 1871.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln loved children, and the Lincolns were not considered to be strict with their own.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] The deaths of Eddie and Willie had profound effects on both parents.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln suffered from "melancholy", a condition now thought to be clinical depression.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1831, Lincoln's father moved the family to a new homestead in Coles County, Illinois, after which Abraham struck out on his own.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] He made his home in New Salem, Illinois, for six years.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] During 1831 and 1832, Lincoln worked at a general store in New Salem.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] He gained a reputation for strength and courage after winning a wrestling match with the leader of a group of ruffians known as the Clary's Grove boys.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1832, he declared his candidacy for the Illinois House of Representatives, though he interrupted his campaign to serve as a captain in the Illinois Militia during the Black Hawk War.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] He was elected the captain of his militia company but did not see combat.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his political campaigning, Lincoln advocated for navigational improvements on the Sangamon River.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] He drew crowds as a raconteur, but he lacked name recognition, powerful friends, and money, and he lost the election.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] When Lincoln returned home from the war, he planned to become a blacksmith but instead purchased a New Salem general store in partnership with William Berry.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Because a license was required to sell customers alcoholic beverages, Berry obtained bartending licenses for Lincoln and himself, and in 1833 the Lincoln–Berry General Store became a tavern as well.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Burlingame wrote that Berry was "an undisciplined, hard-drinking fellow", and Lincoln "was too soft-hearted to deny anyone credit".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Although the economy was booming, the business struggled and went into debt, prompting Lincoln to sell his share.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln served as New Salem's postmaster and later as county surveyor, but he continued his voracious reading and decided to become a lawyer.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Rather than studying in the office of an established attorney, as was customary, Lincoln read law on his own, borrowing legal texts, including Blackstone's *Commentaries* and Chitty's *Pleadings*, from attorney John Todd Stuart.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] He later said of his legal education that he "studied with nobody." He was bestowed an honorary degree of Doctor of Laws by Columbia University in 1861.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] In Lincoln's second state house campaign in 1834, as a supporter of Whig Party leader Henry Clay, he finished second among thirteen candidates running for four places.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln echoed Clay's support for the American Colonization Society, which advocated abolition in conjunction with settling freed slaves in Liberia.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Whigs also favored economic modernization in banking, tariffs to fund internal improvements such as railroads, and urbanization.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln served four terms in the Illinois House of Representatives for Sangamon County.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] In this role, he championed construction of the Illinois and Michigan Canal.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln voted to expand suffrage beyond White landowners to all White men.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] He supported the chartering of the Illinois State Bank, and also led a successful campaign for moving the state capital from Vandalia to Springfield.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] On January 27, 1838, Lincoln delivered an address at the Lyceum in Springfield, after the murder of the anti-slavery newspaper editor Elijah Parish Lovejoy.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] In this ostensibly non-partisan speech, Lincoln attacked Stephen A.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Douglas and the Democratic Party, who the Whigs argued were supporting "mobocracy".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] His speech also attacked anti-abolitionism and racial bigotry.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln was criticized in the press for a planned duel with James Shields, whom he had ridiculed in letters published under the name "Aunt Rebecca".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Although the duel did not take place, Burlingame noted that "the affair embarrassed Lincoln terribly".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1843, Lincoln sought the Whig nomination for Illinois's 7th district seat in the U.S.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Hardin was the winning candidate, though Lincoln convinced the party convention to limit Hardin to one term.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln not only gained the nomination in 1846, but also won the election.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] The only Whig in the Illinois delegation, he was assigned to the Committee on Post Office and Post Roads and the Committee on Expenditures in the War Department.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Giddings on a bill to abolish slavery in the District of Columbia, but dropped the bill when it failed to attract support from most other Whigs.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln spoke against the Mexican–American War (1846–1848), for which he said President James K.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Polk had "some strong motive ... to involve the two countries in a war, and trusting to escape scrutiny, by fixing the public gaze upon the exceeding brightness of military glory—that attractive rainbow, that rises in showers of blood".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] He supported the Wilmot Proviso, a failed 1846 proposal to ban slavery in any U.S. territory won from Mexico.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Polk insisted that Mexican soldiers had begun the war by "invading the territory of the State of Texas ... and shedding the blood of our citizens on our own soil".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his 1847 "spot resolutions", Lincoln rhetorically demanded that Polk tell Congress the exact "spot" where this occurred, but the Polk administration did not respond.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] His approach and rhetoric cost Lincoln political support in his district, and newspapers derisively nicknamed him "spotty Lincoln".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln had pledged in 1846 to serve only one term in the House.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] At the 1848 Whig National Convention, he initially supported Henry Clay and was among the leaders of the Illinois delegation backing Clay, voting for him on the early ballots.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] When it became clear that Clay could not secure the nomination, Lincoln joined other Whigs in shifting support to Zachary Taylor, who won the party's nomination and the presidency in 1848.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] After Taylor won, Lincoln hoped in vain to be appointed commissioner of the United States General Land Office.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] The administration offered to appoint him secretary of the Oregon Territory instead.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] This would have disrupted his legal and political career in Illinois, so he declined and resumed his law practice.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln was admitted to the Illinois bar on September 9, 1836.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] He moved to Springfield and began to practice law under John T.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] He partnered for several years with Stephen T.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Logan and, in 1844, began his practice with William Herndon.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his Springfield practice, according to Donald, Lincoln handled "virtually every kind of business that could come before a prairie lawyer".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] He dealt with many transportation cases in the midst of the nation's western expansion, particularly river barge conflicts under the new railroad bridges.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1849 he received a patent for a flotation device for the movement of riverboats in shallow water and Lincoln initially favored riverboat legal interests, but he represented whoever hired him.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] He represented a bridge company against a riverboat company in *Hurd v.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Rock Island Bridge Company*, a landmark case involving a canal boat that sank after hitting a bridge.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] His patent was never commercialized, but it made Lincoln the only president to hold a patent.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln appeared before the Illinois Supreme Court in 411 cases.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] From 1853 to 1860, one of his largest clients was the Illinois Central Railroad, which Lincoln successfully sued to recover his legal fees.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln represented William "Duff" Armstrong in his 1858 trial for the murder of James Preston Metzker.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] The case is famous for Lincoln's use of a fact established by judicial notice to challenge the credibility of an eyewitness.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] After a witness testified to seeing the crime in the moonlight, Lincoln produced a *Farmers' Almanac* showing the Moon was at a low angle, drastically reducing visibility.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] In an 1859 murder case, he defended "Peachy" Quinn Harrison, the grandson of Peter Cartwright, Lincoln's political opponent.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Harrison was charged with the murder of Greek Crafton who, according to Cartwright, said as he lay dying that he had "brought it upon myself" and that he forgave Harrison.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln angrily protested the judge's initial decision to exclude Cartwright's claim as hearsay.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln argued that the testimony involved a dying declaration and so was not subject to the hearsay rule.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Instead of holding Lincoln in contempt of court as expected, the judge, a Democrat, admitted the testimony into evidence, resulting in Harrison's acquittal.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Compromise of 1850 failed to alleviate tensions over slavery between the slave-holding South and the free North.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] As the slavery debate in the Nebraska and Kansas territories became particularly acrimonious, Illinois Senator Stephen A.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Douglas proposed popular sovereignty as a compromise; the measure would allow the electorate of each territory to decide the status of slavery.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] The legislation alarmed many Northerners, who sought to prevent the spread of slavery, but Douglas's Kansas–Nebraska Act narrowly passed Congress in May 1854.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's Peoria Speech of October 1854, in which he declared his opposition to slavery, was one of an estimated 175 speeches he delivered in the next six years on the topic of excluding slavery from the territories.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's attacks on the Kansas–Nebraska Act marked his return to political life.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Nationally, the Whigs were irreparably split by the Kansas–Nebraska Act and other ineffective efforts to compromise on the slavery issue.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Reflecting on the demise of his party, Lincoln wrote in 1855, "I think I am a whig; but others say there are no whigs, and that I am an abolitionist....
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] I now do no more than oppose the *extension* of slavery." The new Republican Party was formed as a northern party dedicated to anti-slavery, drawing from the anti-slavery wing of the Whig Party and combining Free Soil, Liberty, and anti-slavery Democratic Party members.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln resisted early Republican entreaties, fearing that the new party would become a platform for extreme abolitionists.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln held out hope for rejuvenating the Whigs, though he lamented his party's growing closeness with the nativist Know Nothing movement.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1854, Lincoln was elected to the Illinois legislature, but before the term began he declined to take his seat so that he would be eligible to run in the upcoming U.S.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] At that time, senators were elected by state legislatures.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] After leading in the first six rounds of voting, Lincoln was unable to obtain a majority.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln instructed his backers to vote for Lyman Trumbull, an anti-slavery Democrat who had received few votes in the earlier ballots.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's decision to withdraw enabled his Whig supporters and Trumbull's anti-slavery Democrats to combine and defeat the mainstream Democratic candidate, Joel Aldrich Matteson.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Violent political confrontations in Kansas continued, and opposition to the Kansas–Nebraska Act remained strong throughout the North.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] As the 1856 elections approached, Lincoln joined the Republicans and attended the Bloomington Convention, where the Illinois Republican Party was established.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] The convention platform endorsed Congress's right to regulate slavery in the territories and backed the admission of Kansas as a free state.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln gave the final speech of the convention, calling for the preservation of the Union.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] At the June 1856 Republican National Convention, Lincoln received support to run as vice president, but the party put forward a ticket of John C.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Frémont and William Dayton, which Lincoln supported throughout Illinois.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Democrats nominated James Buchanan and the Know Nothings nominated Millard Fillmore.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Buchanan prevailed, while Republican William Henry Bissell won election as Governor of Illinois, and Lincoln became a leading Republican in Illinois.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Dred Scott was a slave whose master took him from a slave state to a territory that was free as a result of the Missouri Compromise.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] After Scott was returned to the slave state, he petitioned a federal court for his freedom.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] His petition was denied in *Dred Scott v.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Taney wrote in his opinion that the Missouri Compromise was unconstitutional because it infringed on slave owners' property rights by prohibiting them from bringing their slaves into the territories.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] While many Democrats hoped that *Dred Scott* would end the dispute over slavery in the territories, the decision sparked further outrage in the North.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln denounced it as the product of a conspiracy of Democrats to support the Slave Power.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] He argued that the decision was at variance with the Declaration of Independence, which stated that "all men are created equal ... with certain unalienable rights", among them "life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1858, Douglas was up for re-election in the U.S.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Senate, and Lincoln hoped to defeat him.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Many in the party felt that a former Whig should be nominated in 1858, and Lincoln's 1856 campaigning and support of Trumbull had earned him a favor.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] For the first time, Illinois Republicans held a convention to agree upon a Senate candidate, and Lincoln won the nomination with little opposition.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln accepted the nomination with great enthusiasm and zeal.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] The speech created a stark image of the danger of disunion.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Senate campaign featured seven debates between Lincoln and Douglas; they had an atmosphere akin to a prizefight and drew thousands.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln warned that the Slave Power was threatening the values of republicanism, and he accused Douglas of distorting Jefferson's premise that all men are created equal.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his Freeport Doctrine, Douglas argued that, despite the *Dred Scott* decision, which he claimed to support, local settlers, under popular sovereignty, should be free to choose whether to allow slavery in their territory.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] He accused Lincoln of having joined the abolitionists.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Though the Republican legislative candidates won more popular votes, the Democrats won more seats, and the legislature re-elected Douglas.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] However, Lincoln's articulation of the issues had given him a national political presence.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] In the aftermath of the 1858 election, newspapers frequently mentioned Lincoln as a potential Republican presidential candidate.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] While Lincoln was popular in the Midwest, he lacked support in the Northeast and was unsure whether to seek the office.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] In January 1860, Lincoln told a group of political allies that he would accept the presidential nomination if offered and, in the following months, William O.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Stoddard's *Central Illinois Gazette*, the *Chicago Press & Tribune*, and other local papers endorsed his candidacy.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] In February 1860, Henry Ward Beecher invited Lincoln to address his congregation at Plymouth Church in Brooklyn, New York.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln agreed, but the venue shifted to Cooper Union in Manhattan.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Many in the audience thought he appeared awkward and even ugly.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] But Lincoln demonstrated intellectual leadership, which brought him into contention for the presidency.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Journalist Noah Brooks reported, "No man ever before made such an impression on his first appeal to a New York audience".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Historian David Herbert Donald described the speech as "a superb political move for an unannounced presidential aspirant." In response to an inquiry about his ambitions, Lincoln said, "The taste *is* in my mouth a little".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] On May 9–10, 1860, the Illinois Republican State Convention was held in Decatur.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Exploiting his embellished frontier legend of clearing land and splitting fence rails, Lincoln's supporters promoted him as "The Rail Candidate".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] On May 18 at the Republican National Convention in Chicago, Lincoln won the nomination on the third ballot.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] A former Democrat, Hannibal Hamlin of Maine, was nominated for vice president to balance the ticket.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Throughout the 1850s, Lincoln had doubted the prospects of civil war, and his supporters rejected claims that his election would incite secession.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] When Douglas was selected as the candidate of the Northern Democrats, delegates from the Southern slave states elected incumbent Vice President John C.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] A group of former Whigs and Know Nothings formed the Constitutional Union Party and nominated John Bell of Tennessee.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln and Douglas competed for votes in the North, while Bell and Breckinridge found support primarily in the South.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] A nationwide militaristic Republican youth organization, the Wide Awakes, "turned it into one of the most excited elections in American history" and "triggered massive popular enthusiasm", according to the political historian Jon Grinspan.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] People of the Northern states knew the Southern states would vote against Lincoln and rallied supporters for him.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] As Douglas and the other candidates campaigned, Lincoln gave no speeches, relying on the enthusiasm of the Republican Party.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Republican speakers emphasized Lincoln's childhood poverty to demonstrate the power of "free labor", which allowed a common farm boy to work his way to the top by his own efforts.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Though he did not make public appearances, many sought to visit and write to Lincoln.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] In the runup to the election, he took an office in the Illinois state capitol to deal with the influx of attention.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] He also hired John George Nicolay as his personal secretary, who would remain in that role during the presidency.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] On November 6, 1860, Lincoln was elected as the first Republican president.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] His victory was entirely due to his support in the North and West.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] No ballots were cast for him in 10 of the 15 Southern slave states.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln received 1,866,452 votes, or 39.8 percent of the total in a four-way race, carrying the free Northern states, as well as California and Oregon, and winning the electoral vote decisively.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] above the rotunda still under construction.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] following Lincoln's first inauguration portended imminent hostilities.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] After Lincoln's election, secessionists implemented plans to leave the Union before he took office in March 1861.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] On December 20, 1860, South Carolina adopted an ordinance of secession; by February 1, 1861, Florida, Mississippi, Alabama, Georgia, Louisiana, and Texas had followed.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Six of these states declared themselves to be a sovereign nation, the Confederate States of America, selecting Jefferson Davis as its provisional president.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] The upper South and border states (Delaware, Maryland, Virginia, North Carolina, Tennessee, Kentucky, Missouri, and Arkansas) initially rejected the secessionist appeal.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] President Buchanan and President-elect Lincoln refused to recognize the Confederacy, declaring secession illegal.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] On February 11, 1861, Lincoln gave a particularly emotional farewell address upon leaving Springfield for Washington.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln and the Republicans rejected the proposed Crittenden Compromise as contrary to the party's platform of free-soil in the territories.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln said, "I will suffer death before I consent ... to any concession or compromise which looks like buying the privilege to take possession of this government to which we have a constitutional right".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln supported the Corwin Amendment to the U.S.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Constitution, which would have protected slavery in states where it already existed.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] The amendment passed Congress and was awaiting ratification by the required three-fourths of the states when Southern states began to secede.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] On March 4, 1861, in his first inaugural address, Lincoln said that, because he held "such a provision to now be implied constitutional law, I have no objection to its being made express, and irrevocable".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Due to secessionist plots, careful attention was paid to Lincoln's security and the train he took to Washington.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] The president-elect evaded suspected assassins in Baltimore.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] He traveled in disguise, wearing a soft felt hat instead of his customary stovepipe hat and draping an overcoat over his shoulders while hunching to conceal his height.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] On February 23, 1861, he arrived in Washington, D.C., which was placed under military guard.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Many in the opposition press criticized his secretive journey; opposition newspapers mocked Lincoln with caricatures showing him sneaking into the capital.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] The president ended his address with an appeal to the people of the South: "We are not enemies, but friends....
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] The mystic chords of memory, stretching from every battle-field, and patriot grave, to every living heart and hearthstone ... will yet swell the chorus of the Union, when again touched ... by the better angels of our nature".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to Donald, the failure of the Peace Conference of 1861 to attract the attendance of seven of the Confederate states signaled that legislative compromise was not a practical expectation.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] In selecting his cabinet, Lincoln chose the men he found the most competent, even when they had been his opponents for the presidency.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln commented on his thought process, "We need the strongest men of the party in the Cabinet.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] We needed to hold our own people together.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] I had looked the party over and concluded that these were the very strongest men.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Then I had no right to deprive the country of their services." Doris Kearns Goodwin described the group in her 2005 biography of Lincoln as a "team of rivals".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln named his main political opponent, William H.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln made five appointments to the Supreme Court.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Noah Haynes Swayne, a prominent corporate lawyer from Ohio, replaced John McLean after the latter's death in April 1861.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Samuel Freeman Miller, who replaced Peter V.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Daniel, was an avowed abolitionist and received widespread support from Iowa politicians.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] David Davis was Lincoln's campaign manager in 1860 and had served as a judge in the Illinois court circuit where Lincoln practiced.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Democrat Stephen Johnson Field, a previous California Supreme Court justice, provided geographic and political balance.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Taney, Lincoln appointed his former secretary of the treasury, Salmon P.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Chase, to replace Taney as chief justice.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln believed Chase was an able jurist who would support Reconstruction legislation and that his appointment would unite the Republican Party.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] In early April 1861, Major Robert Anderson, commander of Fort Sumter in Charleston, South Carolina, advised that he was nearly out of food.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] After considerable deliberation, Lincoln decided to send provisions; according to Michael Burlingame, he "could not be sure that his decision would precipitate a war, though he had good reason to believe that it might".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] On April 12, 1861, Confederate forces fired on Union troops at Fort Sumter, starting the American Civil War.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] The April 12 and 13 attack on Fort Sumter rallied the Northern public to see military action against the South as necessary to defend the nation.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] On April 15, Lincoln called for 75,000 militiamen to recapture forts, protect Washington, and preserve the Union.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] This call forced states to choose whether to secede or to support the Union.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] North Carolina, Virginia, Tennessee, and Arkansas seceded.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] As the Northern states sent regiments south, on April 19 Baltimore mobs in control of the rail links attacked Union troops who were changing trains.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Local leaders' groups later burned critical rail bridges to the capital and the Army responded by arresting local Maryland officials.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln suspended the writ of *habeas corpus*, allowing arrests without formal charges.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] John Merryman, a Maryland officer arrested for hindering U.S. troop movements, successfully petitioned Supreme Court Chief Justice Taney to issue a writ of *habeas corpus*.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] In an opinion titled *Ex parte Merryman*, Taney, not ruling on behalf of the Supreme Court, wrote that the Constitution authorized only Congress and not the president to suspend habeas corpus.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] But Lincoln engaged in nonacquiescence and persisted with the policy of suspension in select areas.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Under various suspensions, 15,000 civilians were detained without trial; several, including the anti-war Democrat Clement L.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Vallandigham, were tried in military courts for "treasonable" actions, which was condemned as an attack on free speech.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln took executive control of the war and shaped the Union military strategy.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] He responded to the unprecedented political and military crisis as commander-in-chief by exercising unprecedented authority.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] He expanded his war powers, imposed a naval blockade on Confederate ports, disbursed funds before appropriation by Congress, suspended *habeas corpus*, and arrested and imprisoned thousands of suspected Confederate sympathizers.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln gained the support of Congress and the northern public for these actions.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln also had to reinforce Union sympathies in the border slave states and keep the war from becoming an international conflict.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] It was clear from the outset that bipartisan support was essential to success, and that any compromise alienated factions in both political parties.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Copperheads (anti-war Democrats) criticized Lincoln for refusing to compromise on slavery; the Radical Republicans, who demanded harsh treatment against secession, criticized him for moving too slowly to abolish slavery.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] On August 6, 1861, Lincoln signed the Confiscation Act, which authorized judicial proceedings to confiscate and free slaves who were used to support the Confederates.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] The law had little practical effect, but it signaled political support for abolishing slavery.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's war strategy had two priorities: ensuring that Washington was well defended and conducting an aggressive war effort for a prompt, decisive victory.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Twice a week, Lincoln met with his cabinet.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Occasionally, Lincoln's wife, Mary, prevailed on him to take a carriage ride, concerned that he was working too hard.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Early in the war, Lincoln selected civilian generals from varied political and ethnic backgrounds "to secure their and their constituents' support for the war effort and ensure that the war became a national struggle".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] In January 1862, after complaints of inefficiency and profiteering in the War Department, Lincoln replaced Simon Cameron as secretary of war with Edwin Stanton.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Stanton worked more often and more closely with Lincoln than did any other senior official.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to Stanton's biographers Benjamin P.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Thomas and Harold Hyman, "Stanton and Lincoln virtually conducted the war together".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln saw the importance of Vicksburg for control of the Mississippi River valley and understood the necessity of defeating the enemy's army, rather than merely capturing territory.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] In directing the Union's war strategy, Lincoln valued the advice of Winfield Scott, even after his retirement as Commanding General of the United States Army.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] In 1861 Scott proposed the Anaconda Plan, which relied on port blockades and advancing down the Mississippi to subdue the South.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] In June 1862, Lincoln made an unannounced visit to West Point, where he spent five hours consulting with Scott regarding the handling of the war.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Internationally, Lincoln wanted to forestall foreign military aid to the Confederacy.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] He relied on his combative Secretary of State William Seward while working closely with Senate Foreign Relations Committee chairman Charles Sumner.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Navy illegally intercepted a British mail ship, the *RMS Trent*, on the high seas and seized two Confederate envoys.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Although the North celebrated the seizure, Britain protested vehemently, and the Trent Affair threatened war between the Americans and the British.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln ended the crisis by releasing the two diplomats.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] After the Union rout at Bull Run and Winfield Scott's retirement, Lincoln appointed George B.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Early in the war, McClellan created defenses for Washington that were almost impregnable: 48 forts and batteries, with 480 guns manned by 7,200 artillerists.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] He spent months planning his Virginia Peninsula Campaign.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] McClellan's slow progress and excessive precautions frustrated Lincoln.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] McClellan, in turn, blamed the failure of the campaign on Lincoln's cautiousness in having reserved troops for the capital.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] In 1862, Lincoln removed McClellan as general-in-chief; he elevated Henry Halleck to the post and appointed John Pope as head of the new Army of Virginia.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] In the summer of 1862 Pope was soundly defeated at the Second Battle of Bull Run, forcing him to retreat to Washington.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Soon after, the Army of Virginia was disbanded.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Despite his dissatisfaction with McClellan's failure to reinforce Pope, Lincoln restored him to command of all forces around Washington, which included both the Army of the Potomac and the remains of the Army of Virginia.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lee's forces crossed the Potomac River into Maryland, leading to the Battle of Antietam.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] This battle, a Union victory, was among the bloodiest in American history.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] A crisis of command occurred for Lincoln when McClellan then resisted the president's demand that he pursue Lee's withdrawing army, while Don Carlos Buell likewise refused orders to move the Army of the Ohio against rebel forces in eastern Tennessee.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln replaced Buell with William Rosecrans and McClellan with Ambrose Burnside; according to Donald, this was a "shrewd" political move as they were non-partisan—unlike McClellan, a Democrat.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Against presidential advice, Burnside launched an offensive across the Rappahannock River and was defeated by Lee at Fredericksburg in December.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Facing low morale and discontent among the troops, Lincoln replaced Burnside with Joseph Hooker.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Hooker endured heavy casualties at the Battle of Chancellorsville in May, then resigned in June and was replaced by George Meade.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Meade followed Lee north into Pennsylvania and defeated him in the Gettysburg campaign but then failed to effectively block Lee's orderly retreat to Virginia, despite Lincoln's demands.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant captured Vicksburg and gained control of the Mississippi River.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] In May 1863, Lincoln issued the Lieber Code, which governed wartime conduct of the Union Army, defining command responsibility for war crimes and crimes against humanity.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Two Union generals had issued emancipation orders in 1861 and 1862, but Lincoln overrode both: he found that the decision to emancipate was not within the generals' power, and that it might induce loyal border states to secede.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] However, in June 1862, Congress passed an act banning slavery in all federal territories, which Lincoln signed.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] In July, the Confiscation Act of 1862 was enacted, allowing the seizure of slaves from those disloyal to the United States.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] On July 22, 1862, Lincoln reviewed a draft of the Emancipation Proclamation with his cabinet.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Senator Willard Saulsbury Sr. criticized the proclamation, stating that it "would light their author to dishonor through all future generations".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] By contrast, Horace Greeley, editor of the *New-York Tribune*, in his public letter, "The Prayer of Twenty Millions", implored Lincoln to embrace emancipation.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Buttressed by news of the recent Union victory at Antietam, on September 22, 1862, Lincoln issued the preliminary Emancipation Proclamation, which proclaimed that, on January 1, 1863, all persons held as slaves within any state still in rebellion would be free.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] On January 1, 1863, he issued the final Emancipation Proclamation, freeing the slaves in the ten states not then under Union control, exempting areas under such control.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] With the abolition of slavery in the rebel states now a military objective, Union armies advancing south enabled thousands to escape bondage.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Proclamation was immediately denounced by Copperheads, who advocated restoring the union by allowing slavery.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] It was also seen as a betrayal of his promise to Southern Unionists not to tamper with slavery; Emerson Etheridge, then Clerk of the House of Representatives, joined an unsuccessful plot to give the Democrats and Southern Unionists control of the House.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] As a result of the Proclamation, enlisting freedmen became official policy.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] In a letter to Tennessee military governor Andrew Johnson, Lincoln wrote, "The bare sight of fifty thousand armed, and drilled black soldiers on the banks of the Mississippi would end the rebellion at once".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln gave the dedication for the Gettysburg battlefield cemetery on November 19, 1863.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] The address became the most quoted speech in American history.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Following Admiral David Farragut's capture of New Orleans in 1862, and after victories at Gettysburg and Vicksburg, Lincoln proclaimed a national Thanksgiving holiday, to be celebrated on the final Thursday of November 1863.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant's victories at the Battle of Shiloh and in the Vicksburg campaign impressed Lincoln.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Responding to criticism of Grant after Shiloh, Lincoln said, "I can't spare this man.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] He fights." Following Meade's failure to capture Lee's army after Gettysburg and after Grant's success at Chattanooga, Lincoln promoted Grant to commander of all Union armies.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln reacted to Union losses by mobilizing support throughout the North.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Union forces targeted infrastructure—plantations, railroads, and bridges—to weaken the South's morale and fighting ability.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] While Lincoln sanctioned this approach, he emphasized the defeat of the Confederate armies over destruction for its own sake.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant's bloody Overland Campaign turned into a strategic success for the Union despite a number of setbacks.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] But the campaign was the bloodiest in American history: approximately 55,000 casualties on the Union side (including 7,600 deaths), compared to about 33,000 on the Confederate (including 4,200 deaths).
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lee's losses, although lower in absolute numbers, were proportionately higher (over 50%) than Grant's (about 45%).
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] In early April, the Confederate government evacuated Richmond and Lincoln visited the conquered capital.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Amid the turmoil of military actions, on June 30, 1864, Lincoln signed into law the Yosemite Grant, which provided unprecedented federal protection for the area now known as Yosemite National Park.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln and Secretary of the Treasury Salmon Chase faced a challenge in funding a wartime economy.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Congress quickly approved Lincoln's request to assemble an army, even increasing his proposed 400,000 soldiers to 500,000, but both Congress and Chase initially resisted raising taxes.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] After the Union defeat at the First Battle of Bull Run, which collapsed the bond market, Congress passed the Revenue Act of 1861.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] This act imposed the first U.S. federal income tax, creating a flat tax of three percent on annual incomes above $800 ($28,700 in current dollars).
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] As the average urban worker made approximately $600 per year, many were not required to pay income taxes.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln also signed increases to the Morrill Tariff, which had become law in the final months of Buchanan's tenure.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] These tariffs raised import duties considerably and were designed both to increase revenue and to help manufacturers offset the burden of new taxes.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Throughout the war, Congress debated whether to raise additional revenue primarily by increasing tariff rates, which most strongly affected rural areas, or by increasing income taxes, which most affected wealthier individuals; the latter view proved more popular.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] The revenue measures of 1861 proved inadequate for funding the war, forcing Congress to take further action.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] In February 1862, Congress passed the Legal Tender Act, which authorized the minting of $150 million in "greenbacks"—the first banknotes issued by the U.S. government since the end of the American Revolution.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Greenbacks were not backed by gold or silver, but rather by the government's promise to honor their value.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] By the end of the war, $450 million worth of greenbacks were in circulation.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Congress also passed the Revenue Act of 1862, which established an excise tax affecting nearly every commodity, as well as the first national inheritance tax.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] It also added a progressive tax structure to the federal income tax.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] To collect these taxes, Congress created the Office of the Commissioner of Internal Revenue.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Despite the new revenue measures, funding the war remained challenging.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] The government continued to issue greenbacks and borrow large amounts of money, and the U.S. national debt grew from $65 million in 1860 to over $2 billion in 1866.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Revenue Act of 1864 represented a compromise between those who favored a more progressive tax structure and those who favored a flat tax.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] It established a five-percent tax on incomes above $600 and a ten-percent tax on incomes above $10,000, and it raised taxes on businesses.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] In early 1865, Congress reduced the threshold for ten-percent taxation to incomes above $5000.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] By the end of the war, the income tax constituted about one-fifth of the federal government's revenue, though it was intended as a temporary wartime measure.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln also took action against wartime fraud, signing into law the False Claims Act of 1863.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] This statute imposed penalties for false claims and made it possible for private citizens to file false-claim (*qui tam*) lawsuits on behalf of the U.S. government and share in the recovery.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Hoping to stabilize the currency, Lincoln convinced Congress to pass the National Banking Act in 1863, established the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency to oversee "national banks," which were subject to federal, rather than state, regulation.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] In return for investing a third of their capital in federal bonds, national banks were authorized to issue federal banknotes.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] After Congress imposed a tax on private banknotes in March 1865, federal banknotes became the dominant form of paper currency.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Other economic policies passed under Lincoln included the 1862 Homestead Act, which made millions of acres of government-held land in the West available for purchase at low cost.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] The 1862 Morrill Land-Grant Colleges Act provided government grants for agricultural colleges in each state.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Pacific Railway Acts of 1862 and 1864 granted federal support for the construction of the United States' first transcontinental railroad, which was completed in 1869.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] At the start of the war, Russia was the lone great power to support the Union, while the other European powers had varying degrees of sympathy for the Confederacy.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to the historian Dean Mahin, Lincoln had "limited familiarity with diplomatic practices" but exerted "substantial influence on U.S. diplomacy" as the Union attempted to avoid war with Britain and France.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln appointed diplomats to try to persuade European nations not to recognize the Confederacy.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's policy succeeded: all foreign nations were officially neutral throughout the Civil War, with none recognizing the Confederacy.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Some European leaders looked for ways to exploit the inability of the U.S. to enforce the Monroe Doctrine opposing European colonial intervention in the Americas: Spain invaded the Dominican Republic in 1861, while France established a puppet regime in Mexico.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] However, many in Europe also hoped for a quick end to the war, both for humanitarian reasons and because of the economic disruption it caused.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] The European aristocracy was "absolutely gleeful in pronouncing the American debacle as proof that the entire experiment in popular government had failed", according to Don H.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Union diplomats initially had to explain that the United States was not committed to ending slavery, and instead they argued that secession was unconstitutional.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Confederate spokesmen were more successful by ignoring slavery and instead focusing on their struggle for independence, their commitment to free trade, and the essential role of cotton in the European economy.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Confederacy's hope that cotton exports would compel European interference did not come to fruition, as Britain found alternative sources and maintained economic ties with the Union.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Though the issuance of the Emancipation Proclamation in January 1863 did not immediately end the possibility of European intervention, it rallied European public opinion to the Union by adding abolition as a Union war goal.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Any chance of a European intervention in the war ended with the Union victories at Gettysburg and Vicksburg in July 1863, as European leaders came to believe that the Confederate cause was doomed.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Dole as commissioner of the Bureau of Indian Affairs and made "extensive use of Indian Service positions to reward political supporters", according to the historian Thomas Britten.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's policies largely focused on assimilation of Native Americans and diminishing tribal landholdings, consistent with those of his predecessors, but his direct involvement in Native American affairs was unclear.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] His administration faced difficulties guarding Western settlers, railroads, and telegraph lines from Native American attacks.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Tensions arose with the Dakota people due to American treaty violations, unfair trading, and government practices that led to starvation.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] In August 1862, the Dakota War broke out in Minnesota.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Hundreds of settlers were killed and 30,000 were displaced from their homes.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Some feared incorrectly that it might represent a Confederate conspiracy to start a war on the Northwestern frontier.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln ordered thousands of paroled prisoners of war be sent to put down the uprising.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] When the Confederacy protested, Lincoln revoked the policy and none arrived in Minnesota.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln sent Pope as commander of the new Department of the Northwest.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Appointed as a state militia colonel, Henry Hastings Sibley eventually defeated the Dakota chief Little Crow at the Battle of Wood Lake.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] A war crimes trial led by Sibley sentenced 303 Dakota warriors to death; the legal scholar Carol Chomsky described the trial as "a study in military injustice" designed to "guarantee an unjust outcome".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln pardoned all but 39 of the condemned warriors, and, with one execution suspended, the remaining 38 were hanged in the largest mass execution in U.S. history.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Congressman Alexander Ramsey told Lincoln in 1864 that he would have received more re-election support in Minnesota had he executed all 303 warriors.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln responded, "I could not afford to hang men for votes." Lincoln called for reform of federal Indian policy but prioritized the war and Reconstruction.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Changes were made in response to the Sand Creek Massacre of November 1864, prioritizing peaceful administration of Native affairs and condemning those encroaching on Native territory, but not until after Lincoln's death.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln ran for re-election in 1864; the Democratic nominee was former general McClellan.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Republican Party selected Andrew Johnson, a War Democrat, as Lincoln's running mate.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] To broaden his coalition to include War Democrats as well as Republicans, Lincoln ran under the new label of the National Union Party.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant's bloody stalemates and Confederate victories such as the Battle of the Crater damaged Lincoln's re-election prospects, and many Republicans feared defeat.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln prepared a confidential memorandum pledging that, if he should lose the election, he would "co-operate with the President-elect, as to save the Union between the election and the inauguration; as he will have secured his election on such ground that he cannot possibly save it afterwards".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Victories at Atlanta in September and in the Shenandoah Valley in October turned public opinion, and Lincoln was re-elected with 55.1 percent of the popular vote as well as 212 electoral votes to McClellan's 21.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] As Grant continued to weaken Lee's forces, efforts to discuss peace began.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Stephens, the Confederate vice president, and two other Confederate officials met with Lincoln and Seward at Hampton Roads.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln refused to negotiate with the Confederacy as a coequal, and the only agreement reached at the meeting concerned the exchange of prisoners.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's second inauguration took place on March 4, 1865; historian Mark Noll places his second inaugural address "among the small handful of semi-sacred texts by which Americans conceive their place in the world"; it is inscribed in the Lincoln Memorial.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] A month later, on April 9, Lee surrendered to Grant at Appomattox, signaling the end of the war.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] It triggered a series of subsequent surrenders across the South—in North Carolina, Alabama, and the trans-Mississippi Theater—and finally at sea with the surrender of the CSS *Shenandoah* in November 1865.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Reconstruction began before the war's end, as Lincoln and his associates considered the reintegration of the nation, and the fates of Confederate leaders and freed slaves.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] When a general asked Lincoln how the defeated Confederates were to be treated, Lincoln replied, "Let 'em up easy"; he focused not on blame for the war but on rebuilding.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Determined to reunite the nation and not alienate the South, Lincoln urged that speedy elections under generous terms be held.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] His Amnesty Proclamation of December 8, 1863, offered pardons to those who had not held a Confederate civil office and had not mistreated Union prisoners, if they signed an oath of allegiance.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln led the moderates in Reconstruction policy and was opposed by the Radicals, under Thaddeus Stevens, Charles Sumner and Benjamin Wade, who otherwise remained Lincoln's allies.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] As Southern states fell, they needed leaders while their administrations were being restored.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] In Tennessee and Arkansas, Lincoln appointed Andrew Johnson and Frederick Steele, respectively, as military governors.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] In Louisiana, Lincoln ordered Nathaniel P.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Banks to promote a plan that would reestablish statehood when 10 percent of the voters agreed, but only if the reconstructed states abolished slavery.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Democratic opponents accused Lincoln of using the plan to ensure his and the Republicans' political aspirations.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Radicals denounced his policy as too lenient and passed their own plan, the 1864 Wade–Davis Bill, but Lincoln pocket-vetoed it.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Radicals retaliated by refusing to seat elected representatives from Louisiana, Arkansas, and Tennessee.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] After implementing the Emancipation Proclamation, Lincoln increased pressure on Congress to outlaw slavery nationwide with a constitutional amendment.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] By December 1863 an amendment was brought to Congress.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Senate passed it on April 8, 1864, but the first vote in the House of Representatives fell short of the required two-thirds majority.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Passage became part of Lincoln's re-election platform, and after his re-election, the second attempt in the House passed on January 31, 1865.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] After ratification by three-fourths of the states in December 1865, it became the Thirteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution, abolishing "slavery [and] involuntary servitude, except as a punishment for crime".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln announced a Reconstruction plan that involved short-term military administration, pending readmission under the control of southern Unionists.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] He also signed Senator Charles Sumner's Freedmen's Bureau bill that set up a temporary federal agency designed to meet the immediate needs of former slaves.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] The law opened land for a lease of three years with the ability for the freedmen to purchase title.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Eric Foner argues that "Lincoln did not see Reconstruction as an opportunity for a sweeping political and social revolution beyond emancipation.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] He had long made clear his opposition to the confiscation and redistribution of land." However, the Lincoln scholar Phillip S.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Paludan suggests that at the end of his life Lincoln was moving towards a more radical position, particularly with regards to freedmen's rights.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] John Wilkes Booth was a well-known actor and a Confederate spy from Maryland; although he never joined the Confederate army, he had contacts within the Confederate secret service.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] After attending Lincoln's last public address, on April 11, 1865, in which Lincoln stated his preference that the franchise be conferred on some Black men, specifically "on the very intelligent, and on those who serve our cause as soldiers", Booth plotted to assassinate the President.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] When Booth learned of the Lincolns' intent to attend a play with Grant, he planned to assassinate Lincoln and Grant at Ford's Theatre.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln and his wife attended the play *Our American Cousin* on the evening of April 14.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] At the last minute, Grant decided to go to New Jersey to visit his children instead.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] At 10:15 pm, Booth entered Lincoln's theater box, crept up from behind, and fired at the back of Lincoln's head, mortally wounding him.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's guest, Major Henry Rathbone, momentarily grappled with Booth, but Booth stabbed him and escaped.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] After being attended by Charles Leale and two other doctors, Lincoln was taken across the street to Petersen House.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] He remained in a coma for nine hours and died at 7:22 am on April 15.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's body was wrapped in a flag and placed in a coffin, which was loaded into a hearse and escorted to the White House by Union soldiers.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Johnson was sworn in as president later that day.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Two weeks later, Booth was located, shot, and killed at a farm in Virginia by Sergeant Boston Corbett.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] From April 19 to 20, Lincoln lay in state, first in the White House and then in the Capitol rotunda.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] The caskets containing Lincoln's body and the body of his third son Willie then traveled for two weeks on a funeral train following a circuitous route from Washington D.C. to Springfield, Illinois, stopping at several cities for memorials attended by hundreds of thousands.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Many others gathered along the tracks as the train passed with bands, bonfires, and hymn singing or in silent grief.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Historians emphasized the widespread shock and sorrow, but noted that some who had hated Lincoln celebrated his death.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Walt Whitman composed four elegies to Lincoln, including "When Lilacs Last in the Dooryard Bloom'd" and "O Captain!
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's body was buried at Oak Ridge Cemetery in Springfield and now lies within the Lincoln Tomb.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln redefined the political philosophy of republicanism in the United States.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Because the Declaration of Independence says that all men have an unalienable right to life, liberty and the pursuit of happiness, he called it the "sheet anchor" of republicanism, at a time when the Constitution was the focus of most political discourse.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] He presented the Declaration as establishing equality as a foundational principle for the United States, which had a significant impact on social and political movements in the U.S. into the 20th century.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] As a Whig activist, Lincoln was a spokesman for business interests, favoring high tariffs, banks, infrastructure improvements, and railroads, in opposition to Jacksonian democrats.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Nevertheless, Lincoln admired Andrew Jackson's steeliness and patriotism, and adopted the Jacksonian "belief in the common man".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] As a young man, Lincoln was a religious skeptic.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] However, he was deeply familiar with the Bible; throughout his public career, he often quoted scripture.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] His three most famous speeches—the House Divided Speech, the Gettysburg Address, and his second inaugural address—all contain such quotes.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] In the 1840s, Lincoln subscribed to the Doctrine of Necessity, a belief that the human mind was controlled by a higher power.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] After the death of his son Edward in 1850, Lincoln more frequently expressed a dependence on God.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] He never joined a church, although he and his wife frequently attended First Presbyterian Church in Springfield, Illinois, beginning in 1852.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] While president, Lincoln often attended services at the New York Avenue Presbyterian Church in Washington, D.C.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] The death of his son Willie in February 1862 may have caused him to look toward religion for solace.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's frequent use of religious imagery and language toward the end of his life may have reflected his own personal beliefs or might have been a device to reach his audiences, who were mostly evangelical Protestants.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Sources differ in how they describe his religious beliefs.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Stephen Mansfield describes "an atheist or religiously skeptical Lincoln" as "the prevailing view", although he argues that "there was a spiritual journey of some kind in Abraham Lincoln's life".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Richard Carwardine writes that "Many elements of the inner Lincoln, including his personal faith ... necessarily remain a puzzle".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's last words were, as reported by his wife, "There is no place I so much desire to see as Jerusalem".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to Michael Burlingame, Lincoln was described as "awkward" and "gawky" as a youth.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] In adolescence he was tall and strong, participating in jumping, throwing, wrestling, and footraces, and demonstrating exceptional strength.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Burlingame notes that Lincoln's clothes "were typically rough and suited to the frontier", with a gap between his shoes, socks, and pants that often exposed six or more inches of his shin; "he cared little about fashion".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln was a slender six feet four inches, with a high-pitched voice.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] While he is usually portrayed bearded, he did not grow a beard until 1860 at the suggestion of 11-year-old Grace Bedell; he was the first U.S. president to do so.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Herndon described Lincoln's face as "long, narrow, sallow, and cadaverous", his cheeks as "leathery and saffron-colored".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln described himself as having a "dark complexion, with coarse black hair".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Although Lincoln's features were said to be "unpleasant to behold," Walt Whitman "wrote that Lincoln's face was 'so awful ugly it becomes beautiful.'" Lincoln's detractors also remarked on his appearance.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Among the illnesses that Lincoln is either documented or speculated to have suffered from are depression, smallpox, and malaria.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] He took blue mass pills, which contained mercury, to treat melancholy or hypochondriasis; this could have resulted in mercury poisoning.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] Several claims have been made that Lincoln's health was declining before his assassination, as photographs of Lincoln appear to show weight loss and facial changes.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p02] It has been proposed that he could have had a rare genetic disorder such as Marfan syndrome or multiple endocrine neoplasia type 2B.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p03] In surveys of U.S. scholars ranking presidents since 1948, the top three presidents are generally Lincoln, George Washington, and Franklin D.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p03] A 2004 study found that scholars in history and politics ranked Lincoln number one, while legal scholars placed him second after Washington.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p03] Kennedy, and Ronald Reagan were the top-ranked presidents in eight public opinion surveys by Gallup.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln's assassination made him a national martyr.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p03] He was viewed by abolitionists as a champion of human liberty.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p03] Many, though not all, in the South considered Lincoln to be a man of outstanding ability.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p03] In the New Deal era, liberals honored Lincoln as an advocate of the common man who they claimed would have supported the welfare state, and Lincoln became a favorite of liberal intellectuals across the world.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p03] The high point came in 1922 with the dedication of the Lincoln Memorial on the National Mall in Washington, D.C.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p03] The Black orator and former slave Frederick Douglass stated that in "his company, I was never reminded of my humble origin, or of my unpopular color", and Lincoln has long been known as the Great Emancipator.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p03] By the late 1960s, some Black intellectuals denied that Lincoln deserved that title.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lerone Bennett Jr. won wide attention when he called Lincoln a White supremacist in 1968.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p03] He noted that Lincoln used ethnic slurs and argued that Lincoln opposed social equality and proposed that freed slaves voluntarily move to another country.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p03] Defenders of Lincoln highlighted his condemnation of slavery and his contributions to its abolition, casting his delays and racist rhetoric as concessions to political necessity rather than reflections of his personal beliefs.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln has also been characterized as a folk hero and as "Honest Abe".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p03] David Herbert Donald opined in his 1996 biography that Lincoln was endowed with the personality trait of negative capability, attributed to extraordinary leaders who were "capable of being in uncertainties ... without any irritable reaching after fact and reason".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln has often been portrayed by Hollywood, almost always in a flattering light; the film historian Melvyn Stokes writes that "moviemakers have commonly used Lincoln primarily as a metaphor for ideas and values they approved".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln's portrait appears on two denominations of United States currency, the penny and the $5 bill.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p03] He appears on postage stamps across the world, including in Ghana, Honduras, China, Haiti, Nicaragua, Colombia, and Argentina.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p03] He has been memorialized in many town, city, and county names, including the capital of Nebraska.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p03] The United States Navy has named three vessels after Lincoln, including the *Nimitz*-class aircraft carrier USS *Abraham Lincoln* (CVN-72).
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p03] The Lincoln Memorial in Washington, D.C., is one of the most visited National Park Service sites in the country.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p03] Memorials in Springfield, Illinois, include the Abraham Lincoln Presidential Library and Museum, Lincoln's home, and his tomb.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p03] A carving of Lincoln appears with those of three other presidents on Mount Rushmore, which receives about 3 million visitors a year.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p03] A statue of Lincoln completed by Augustus Saint-Gaudens stands in Lincoln Park, Chicago, with recastings given as diplomatic gifts standing in Parliament Square, London, and Parque Lincoln, Mexico City.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p03] Several states commemorate "Presidents' Day" as "Washington–Lincoln Day".
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln has been extensively portrayed in media.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p03] Early works, such as *Abraham Lincoln's Clemency* (1910), attempted to mythologize him, emphasizing his mercifulness.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p03] Works from the Great Depression era, such as *Young Mr.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln* (1939), embellished his early struggles and folksiness.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p03] The 1938 play *Abe Lincoln in Illinois* won a Pulitzer Prize and was adapted in film.
[src:albert-a-michelson/abraham-lincoln-p03] After a marked decrease in film portrayals between 1941 and 1999, Daniel Day-Lewis won the Academy Award for Best Actor for his portrayal in *Lincoln*, a 2012 biographical film directed by Steven Spielberg.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] Albert Abraham Michelson was born on December 19, 1852, in Strelno (now Strzelno, Poland), Prussia, into a Polish-Jewish family.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] He moved to the United States with his parents in 1855, at the age of 2.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] He grew up in the mining towns of Murphy's Camp, California, and Virginia City, Nevada, where his father was a merchant.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] His family was non-religious, and Michelson himself was a lifelong agnostic.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] He spent his high school years in San Francisco in the home of his aunt, Henriette Levy (née Michelson), who was the mother of author Harriet Lane Levy.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] His sister was the novelist Miriam Michelson.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] Grant awarded Michelson a special appointment to the U.S.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] During his four years as a midshipman at the Academy, he excelled in optics, heat, climatology and technical drawing.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] After graduating in 1873 and two years at sea, he returned to the Naval Academy in 1875 to become an instructor in physics and chemistry until 1879, when he was posted to the Nautical Almanac Office, Washington (part of the United States Naval Observatory) to work with Simon Newcomb.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] The following year, he took a leave of absence to continue his studies in Europe; he visited the universities of Berlin and Heidelberg in Germany, and the Collège de France and École polytechnique in Paris, France.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was fascinated with the sciences, in particular the problem of measuring the speed of light.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] While in Annapolis, he conducted his first experiments on the speed of light as part of a class demonstration in 1877.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] His Annapolis experiment was refined, and in 1879, he measured the speed of light in air to be 299864±51 kilometres per second, and estimated the speed of light in vacuum as 299940 km/s, or 186380 mi/s.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] After two years of studies in Europe, he resigned from the Navy in 1881.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] In 1883, he was appointed Professor of Physics at the Case School of Applied Science in Cleveland, Ohio, and concentrated on developing an improved interferometer.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] In 1887, he and Edward Morley carried out the famous Michelson–Morley experiment, which failed to detect evidence of the existence of the luminiferous ether.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] He later moved on to use astronomical interferometers in the measurement of stellar diameters and in measuring the separations of binary stars.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] In 1890, Michelson became a professor at Clark University in Worcester, Massachusetts.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] In 1892, he was appointed Professor and the first head of the Department of Physics at the newly-organized University of Chicago, where he remained until his retirement in 1929.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] Michelson returned to military service in the closing months of World War I as a Lieutenant Commander in the Naval Reserve, serving in the Bureau of Ordnance.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] He was promoted to Commander in the reserve in May 1919 and was recalled briefly to active duty in the 9th Naval District before being released from service on September 30, 1921.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] Michelson died on May 9, 1931, in Pasadena, California, at the age of 78.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was fascinated by light all his life.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] Once asked why he studied light, he reputedly said, "because it's so much fun".
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] As early as 1869, while serving as an officer in the United States Navy, Michelson started planning a repeat of the rotating-mirror method of Léon Foucault for measuring the speed of light, using improved optics and a longer baseline.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] He conducted some preliminary measurements using largely improvised equipment in 1878, about the same time that his work came to the attention of Simon Newcomb, director of the Nautical Almanac Office who was already advanced in planning his own study.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] Michelson's formal experiments took place in June and July 1879.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] He constructed a frame building along the north sea wall of the Naval Academy to house the machinery.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] Michelson published his result of 299,910 ± 50 km/s in 1879 before joining Newcomb in Washington DC to assist with his measurements there.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] Thus began a long professional collaboration and friendship between the two.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] Simon Newcomb, with his more adequately funded project, obtained a value of 299,860 ± 30 km/s, just at the extreme edge of consistency with Michelson's.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] Michelson continued to "refine" his method and in 1883 published a measurement of 299,853 ± 60 km/s, rather closer to that of his mentor.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] In 1906, a novel electrical method was used by E.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] Rosa and the National Bureau of Standards to obtain a value for the speed of light of 299,781 ± 10 km/s.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] Though this result has subsequently been shown to be severely biased by the poor electrical standards in use at the time, it seems to have set a fashion for rather lower measured values.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] From 1920, Michelson started planning a definitive measurement from the Mount Wilson Observatory, using a baseline to Lookout Mountain, a prominent bump on the south ridge of Mount San Antonio ("Old Baldy"), some 22 miles distant.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] In 1922, the United States Coast and Geodetic Survey began two years of painstaking measurement of the baseline using the recently available invar tapes.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] With the baseline length established in 1924, measurements were carried out over the next two years to obtain the published value of 299,796 ± 4 km/s.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] Famous as the measurement is, it was beset by problems, not least of which was the haze created by the smoke from forest fires which blurred the mirror image.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] The now-famous Michelson–Morley experiment also influenced the affirmation attempts of peer Albert Einstein's theory of general relativity and special relativity, using similar optical instrumentation.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] These instruments and related collaborations included the participation of fellow physicists Dayton Miller, Hendrik Lorentz, and Robert Shankland.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] The period after 1927 marked the advent of new measurements of the speed of light using novel electro-optic devices, all substantially lower than Michelson's 1926 value.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] Michelson sought another measurement, but this time in an evacuated tube to avoid difficulties in interpreting the image owing to atmospheric effects.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] In 1929, he began a collaboration with Francis G.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] Pease and Fred Pearson to perform a measurement in a 1.6 km tube 3 feet in diameter at the Irvine Ranch near Santa Ana, California.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] In multiple reflections the light path was increased to 5 miles.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] For the first time in history the speed of light was measured in an almost perfect vacuum of 0.5 mm of mercury.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] Michelson died with only 36 of the 233 measurement series completed and the experiment was subsequently beset by geological instability and condensation problems before the result of 299774±11 km/s, consistent with the prevailing electro-optic values, was published posthumously in 1935.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] During June and early July 1879, Michelson refined experimental arrangements from those developed by Hippolyte Fizeau and Léon Foucault.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] For instance, he adopted a steel measuring tape with a said length of 100 feet and he intended to measure tens of times across the distance; still, he measured its length against a copy of the official standard yard to find out it as 100.006 feet, thus eliminating a systematic error, albeit small.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] Aside from the efforts to reduce as much as possible the systematic errors, repeated measurements were performed at multiple levels to obtain more accurate results.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] To realize that, he also strived to have each measurement not influencing each other, thus being mutually independent random variables.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] A statistical model for repeated measurements with the assumption of independence or identical distributions is unrealistic.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] In the case of light speed study, each measurement is approached as the sum of quantity of interest and measurement error.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] The law of large numbers suggests to estimate the expectation by the sample mean.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] In 1887, he collaborated with colleague Edward Williams Morley of Western Reserve University, now part of Case Western Reserve University, in the Michelson–Morley experiment.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] Their experiment for the expected motion of the Earth relative to the aether, the hypothetical medium in which light was supposed to travel, resulted in a null result.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] Surprised, Michelson repeated the experiment with greater and greater precision over the next years, but continued to find no ability to measure the aether.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] The Michelson–Morley results were immensely influential in the physics community, leading Hendrik Lorentz to devise his now-famous Lorentz contraction equations as a means of explaining the null result.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] There has been some historical controversy over whether Albert Einstein was aware of the Michelson–Morley results when he developed his theory of special relativity, which pronounced the aether to be "superfluous".
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] In a later interview, Einstein said of the Michelson–Morley experiment, "I was not conscious it had influenced me directly ...
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] I guess I just took it for granted that it was true." Regardless of Einstein's specific knowledge, the experiment is today considered the canonical experiment in regards to showing the lack of a detectable aether.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] The precision of their equipment allowed Michelson and Morley to be the first to get precise values for the fine structure in the atomic spectral lines for which in 1916 Arnold Sommerfeld gave a theoretical explanation, introducing the fine-structure constant.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] Pease made the first measurement of the diameter of a star other than the Sun.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] Michelson had invented astronomical interferometry and built such an instrument at the Mount Wilson Observatory which was used to measure the diameter of the red giant Betelgeuse.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] A periscope arrangement was used to direct light from two subpupils, separated by up to 20 feet (6m), into the main pupil of the 100 inch (2.5m) Hooker Telescope, producing interference fringes observed through the eyepiece.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] The measurement of stellar diameters and the separations of binary stars took up an increasing amount of Michelson's life after this.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] Beginning in the 1970s, astronomical interferometry was revived, with the configurations using two (or more) separate apertures (with diameters small compared to their separation) being often referred to as "Michelson Stellar Interferometry".
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] This was to distinguish it from speckle interferometry, but should not be confused with the Michelson interferometer which is one common *laboratory* interferometer configuration of which the interferometer used in the Michelson–Morley experiment was an instance.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] Michelson's concept of interfering light from two relatively small apertures separated by a substantial distance (but with that distance, or *baseline*, now often as long as hundreds of meters) is employed at modern operational observatories such as VLTI, CHARA and the U.S.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] Gravitational waves are detected using a Michelson interferometer with a laser light source.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] In 2020 there were three Michelson interferometer gravitational wave detectors operational, and a fourth under construction.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] These Michelson interferometers have arms 4 kilometers in length, set at 90 degree angles to each other, with the light passing through 1 m diameter vacuum tubes running their entire length.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] A passing gravitational wave will slightly stretch one arm as it shortens the other.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] This is precisely the motion to which these Michelson interferometers are most sensitive.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] As of 2020 fifteen gravitational wave events had been observed using these Michelson interferometers.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] In the 1890s Michelson built a mechanical device called the harmonic analyzer, for computing coefficients of Fourier series and drawing graphs of their partial sums.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] Stratton published a paper about this machine in the *American Journal of Science* in 1898.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] In 1877, Michelson married Margaret Hemingway, daughter of a wealthy New York stockbroker and lawyer and the niece of his commander William T.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] In 1899, Michelson married Edna Stanton.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] He is a great uncle of physicist Peter Michelson.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] In Season 3 Episode 26 of the television series *Bonanza* ("Look to the Stars", broadcast March 18, 1962), Ben Cartwright (Lorne Greene) helps the 16-year-old Michelson (portrayed by 25-year-old Douglas Lambert (1936–1986)) obtain an appointment to the U.S.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] Naval Academy, despite the opposition of the bigoted town schoolteacher (played by William Schallert).
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] *Bonanza* was set in and around Virginia City, Nevada, where Michelson lived with his parents prior to leaving for the Naval Academy.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] In a voice-over at the end of the episode, Greene mentions Michelson's 1907 Nobel Prize.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] The home in which Michelson lived as a child in Murphys Camp, California, was in the store of his father, first on Main Street, across from the Sperry & Perry Hotel, and after the 1859 fire in a store next to the hotel.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] His aunt Bertha Meyers owned a house on Main Street toward the east end of town and Michelson probably visited her family there frequently.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] New Beast Theater Works in collaboration with High Concept Laboratories produced a 'semi-opera' about Michelson, his obsessive working style and its effect on his family life.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] The production ran from February 11 to 26, 2011, in Chicago at The Building Stage.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was portrayed by Jon Stutzman.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] The play was directed by David Maral with music composed by Joshua Dumas.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] Norman Fitzroy Maclean wrote an essay "Billiards Is a Good Game"; published in *The Norman Maclean Reader* (ed.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] Alan Weltzien, 2008), it is an appreciation of Michelson from Maclean's vantage point as a graduate student regularly watching him play billiards.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] The University of Chicago Residence Halls remembered Michelson and his achievements by dedicating 'Michelson House' in his honor.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] Case Western Reserve has dedicated a Michelson House to him, and Michelson Hall (an academic building of science classrooms, laboratories and offices) at the United States Naval Academy also bears his name.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Laboratory at Naval Air Weapons Station China Lake in Ridgecrest, California, is named for him.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] There is a display in the publicly accessible area of the Lab which includes facsimiles of Michelson's Nobel Prize medal, the prize document, and examples of his diffraction gratings.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] In 2017, a newly renovated physics research center at the University of Chicago was renamed in honor of Michelson as well.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] Numerous awards, lectures, and honors have been created in Albert A.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Award presented every year by the Computer Measurement Group; the Albert A.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Award given by the Navy League of the United States; and the Michelson Memorial Lecture Series presented annually by the Division of Mathematics and Science at the U.S.
[src:albert-a-michelson/albert-a-michelson] The Computer Measurement Group gives the annual A.
